<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0797 02-27 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0797,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Says Soldiers Filmed in Beating To Be Court-Martialed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs at end UPDATING with strong Dutch reaction.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After receiving a flood of angry phone calls, the
Israeli Embassy said Friday that four Israeli soldiers shown on
television broadcasts beating two bound Palestinan youths will face
court-martial.
   A CBS-TV segment broadcast earlier Friday on British television
showed the soldiers in the occupied West Bank kicking the youths in
the head and chest before picking up rocks and smashing them down
on arms and legs in an effort to break limbs.
   The embassy said the soldiers involved were detained by military
police, who were investigating the Thursday incident in Nablus.
   The soldiers would be subject to court-martial and if found
guilty would be sent to a military jail, said the embassy.
   ``It is being treated very seriously. But we are satisfied that
this sort of thing is not going on all over the place every day,''
said an embassy spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``There has been much reaction from the British public. We have
had many calls. But people can be assured that at least the wheels
of justice will run their course.''
   Earlier, the Israeli ambassador in London, Yehuda Avner,
promised a full investigation.
   Interviewed on ITN-TV news, he said: ``My reaction is one of
shock.''
   The beating also was shown on television in Denmark and the
Israeli Embassy there was deluged with telephone calls from
outraged viewers.
   The film was shot by Bob Simon of the American CBS-TV network.
At the invitation of the Israelis, Simon later flew by helicopter
to a military camp where he was able to identify the soldiers
involved, according to Press Association, the British domestic news
agency..
   According to TV news reports, the beating kept up for a full 40
minutes and was in direct contravention of orders issued this week
by the army high command that prisoners are not to be beaten if
detained after rioting or violence is over.
   In Israel, Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna, the army's West Bank
commander, said, ``We were shocked and couldn't say a word after we
saw this film.''
   Mitzna said he suspended the unit's deputy commander, a captain,
and ordered the two Arabs released.
   Rioting broke out in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip 11
weeks ago, and scores of Arabs have been killed.
   A Foreign Office spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity
under British procedure, said, ``We have watched the scenes on TV
with shock and horror. ...
   ``The action of the ... soldiers is incompatible with the
professional standards of the Israeli defense forces and shows how
far the Israeli soldiers have been brutalized by their experience.''
   Israel's ambassador to the Netherlands, Zev Sufott, made an
unusual appearance on nationwide television there Friday shortly
after the beating scene was shown on Dutch television.
   ``These are aberrations which, as soon as we hear of them, we go
out and pick them (the perpetrators) up,'' Sufott said in an
interview with the NOS-Journaal news broadcast.
   Anchorwoman Noraly Beyer said that by that time, 150 protest
calls already had been made to the studio.
</TEXT>
