<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--MalpracticeSuit     02-27 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Malpractice Suit,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hospital, Bursing Firm Agree To Pay $925,000</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hospital and a nursing firm will
split the cost of a $925,000 settlement to a woman who sued,
charging malpractice after her stomach blew up like a balloon and
her intestine ruptured, her lawyers said.
   Juanita Johns, 53, reached the settlement this week with
University Medical Center and Medical Personnel Pool of Northeast
Florida Inc., which supplied a private duty nurse for her last
year, attorney Wayne Alford said Friday.
   The suit charged that the nurse, ordered by a doctor to place a
tube down Mrs. Johns' throat to remove intestinal gas, incorrectly
hooked up a pump, causing air pressure that blew a hole in the
patient's intestine.
   Mrs. Johns, who continues to suffer infections and has a
disfiguring scar on her abdomen, will receive $150,000 from the
hospital and $775,000 from the nursing pool, said Alford and fellow
attorney John Kalil.
</TEXT>
