<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     02-27 0822</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cost Of Producing Sugarbeets Lower In Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Agriculture Department study of 1984 yields
and expenses shows that sugarbeets can be produced at lower costs
in the Midwest than in some areas of the West, as a rule.
   The study involved seven regions that produce nearly all the
U.S. sugarbeets on about 8,700 farms. Overall, the department's
Economic Research Service reported Friday that it cost an average
of $30.30 per net ton to produce beets. The range, however, was
between $24 and $35 per ton.
   ``About 60 percent of the 1984 U.S. sugarbeet crop was produced
at a cost below the U.S. average price support of $31.63 per ton,''
the report said. ``The producers received a weighted average price
of $33.90 a net ton, ranging from $23.30 in Region 3 (Colorado,
Nebraska and southeastern Wyoming) to $37.10 in Region 6 (eastern
Idaho).''
   Most beet producers in Region 3 operated at a loss because of
the closing of several processing plants by the Great Western Sugar
Co., the report said.
   ``Sugarbeets are a high-value crop, but incomes vary widely
among producers because of differences in input costs, yields,
risks and non-farm income,'' the report said. ``Climatic extremes
in the widely disparate sugarbeet production regions may create
highly variable incomes from region to region or from year to
year.''
   The study of 1984 costs, by region, showed:
   _Region 1, Michigan and Ohio, 10.8 percent of the U.S. sugarbeet
acreage; government support of $27.79 per net ton; actual price
received by growers, $32.95 per ton; average cost of production,
$24.02 per ton.
   _Region 2, Minnesota and eastern North Dakota, 35.2 percent of
the U.S. acreage; support of $32.24 per ton; actual price received
by growers, $36 per ton; average cost of production, $25.66 per ton.
   _Region 3, Colorado, Nebraska and southeastern Wyoming, 12.8
percent of the acreage; support of $31.23 per ton; actual price
received by growers, $23.30 per ton; average cost of production,
$28.06 per ton.
   _Region 4, New Mexico and Texas, was not included in the study.
   _Region 5, Montana, northwestern Wyoming and northwestern North
Dakota, 5 percent of the acreage; support of $31.37 per ton; actual
price received by growers, $35.40 per ton; average cost of
production, $34.26 per ton.
   _Region 6, eastern Idaho, 7.4 percent of the acreage; support of
$31.05 per ton; actual price received by growers, $37.10 per ton;
average cost of production, $34.87 per ton.
   _Region 7, western Idaho and Oregon, 6.5 percent of the acreage;
support of $31.05 per ton; actual price received by growers, $36.90
per ton; average cost of production, $34.68 per ton.
   _Region 8, California, 18.8 percent of the acreage; support of
$32.98 per ton; actual price received by growers, $35.10 per ton;
average cost of production, $34.57 per ton.
  
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The use of cotton by domestic textile
manufacturers is at the highest level since the early 1970s, but an
Agriculture Department analysis says the price outlook for
producers is uncertain.
   In the 1987 marketing year that ended last July 31, nearly 7.5
million bales of cotton were used by mills, up from 6.4 million in
1986. As it looks now, 1988 mill use is headed for another gain to
around 7.8 million bales.
   But imports of cotton textiles also are up, totaling an
equivalent of 4.9 million bales in 1987, a 22 percent increase from
1986, the department's Economic Research Service said Friday.
   Meanwhile, U.S. exports of raw cotton are expected to be around
7 million bales in the 1988 marketing year, an increase of 300,000
bales from 1987, the agency said in its new outlook report.
   Based on Jan. 1 indications, the 1987 cotton harvest _ which
goes into the overall supply for the 1988 marketing year _ is
expected to yield 14.7 million bales, up from 9.7 million bales in
1986.
   Cotton prices moved up last year because of the tighter supply
and rising demand. The U.S. spot price, for example, rose above 77
cents per pound, the report said. But since last August, prices
have dropped 17 to 20 cents.
   ``The larger-than-expected 1987 U.S. crop, the potential for
increased acreage and production in 1988, and concern about the
economy's performance have pressured prices lower this season,''
the report said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Milk production last year declined 1 percent
to less than 142.5 billion pounds from a revised 1986 record of
143.8 billion pounds, the Agriculture Department says.
   Previously, USDA had estimated 1987 milk output at about 142.9
billion pounds and the 1986 record at 144.1 billion.
   The new estimates were in a monthly report Friday on milk
production, which showed January output running about 3 percent
above a year ago in the major dairy states.
   Department economists say 1988 milk production is expected to
rise by 1 percent to 3 percent, which could push output for the
year to another record level.
</TEXT>
