<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 0229EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Romanian-Rights     02-27 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Romanian-Rights,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Romania Tells US To Cancel Special Trade Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Romanian government has decided to
renounce special trade benefits from the United States rather than
comply with American human rights demands, the State Department
says.
   As a result of abandoning the 13-year policy, Romania could lose
up to $250 million in commerce with the United States this year.
   At the same time, the United States will lose an economic weapon
the Reagan administration has claimed to be effective in pressuring
Romania to improve the plight of its people.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley announced Friday
that Romania informed the United States through diplomatic channels
that it had decided to renounce its receipt of most-favored-nation
trading status. That status has kept tariffs on Romanian goods at
levels lower than those for products from most other Soviet-allied
countries.
   The benefits will end July 2 and Romania also will lose
eligibility for U.S. government-supported export credits through
the Commodity Credit Corp. or the Export-Import Bank, Mrs. Oakley
said.
   She said Romania estimates the action will cause a $250 million
annual reduction in Romanian sales to the United States, which
totaled $775 million in 1987.
   U.S. exports to Romania are worth $200 million annually, of
which half are agriculture products, and Mrs. Oakley said the
competitiveness of these exports also will suffer.
   Rep. Christopher Smith, R-N.J., a House Foreign Affairs
Committee member who visited Bucharest last year, said in an
interview that the decision by Romanian President Nicolae Ceausescu
to renounce the benefit was ``to pre-empt the annual scrutiny of
Romania's human rights record, which is deplorable.''
   ``He's cutting off his nose to spite his face,'' Smith said of
Ceausescu. ```We don't want to end the relationship. We just want
them to stop the trashing of human rights.''
   In recent years, U.S. diplomats have conferred with the
Ceausescu government on steps Romania was expected to take to get
most-favored-nation status. The message was simple: improve rights
or lose income.
   Under the 1975 Jackson-Vanik amendment, communist countries
otherwise ineligible for most-favored-nation status can win the
benefit from Congress if the president certifies the country has
fair emigration policies.
   Since enactment of the amendment, which was designed to spur
emigration of Jews and other ethnic groups from the Soviet bloc,
only Hungary, Poland and Romania have received the benefits.
   While the statute links the benefits only to emigration
policies, a growing dissatisfaction on Capitol Hill with Romania's
overall human rights record in recent months has prompted bills
cutting off the privileges this year.
   Besides Romania's longstanding suppression of free speech,
assembly, political opposition and other rights, senators and
congressmen said, there had been little movement on U.S. demands
for a loosening of control over religious minorities.
   Deputy Secretary of State John C. Whitehead, who met Ceausescu
in Bucharest three weeks ago, informed the Romanian leader of U.S.
dissatisfaction with human rights policies.
   Ceausescu's reply appeared to presage the decision announced
Friday. Whitehead told reporters after the meeting that in response
to his comments about Romanian rights, Ceausescu said, in essence:
stop meddling in Romania's internal affairs.
   Mrs. Oakley said that despite the halting of the
most-favored-nation process, Romania ``has authoritatively stated
to us that it will continue to allow emigration for family
reunification purposes, without relation to economic ties with the
United States. We welcome this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
