<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Politics-Quotes     02-27 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Politics-Quotes,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quotes From Presidential Candidates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some comments Friday from candidates
for the presidency:
   
   GEORGE BUSH, on Panama's military strong man Manuel Antonio
Noriega: ``Noriega's gone bad, and he's proven he's trafficked in
narcotics. ... Noriega should go and in my view he will go.''
   
   JACK KEMP, saying he thinks Noriega should be ousted because a
friendly government in Panama is essential: ``Noriega ...
represents a threat to the Panama Canal.''
   
   RICHARD GEPHARDT, saying Eastern Airlines cares more about
profits than its employees: ``We will stop the attitude that the
way to make profits is to take them out of the hides of employees.''
   Eastern Airlines spokesman Robin Matell called Gephardt's
remarks ``a cheap attempt to get votes in the upcoming presidential
primaries.''
   
   MICHAEL DUKAKIS, stressing education and urging good jobs and
opportunity for all: ``It's going to take hard workers, not high
rollers, to get America moving again.''
   
   PAT ROBERTSON, speaking to students at a Christian academy: ``(I
want) to see America once again return to the fundamental faith
that she had, the faith of our fathers, to go back to our faith in
God and go back to individual self-reliance, to go back to a
feeling of community, to go back to strong family values.''
   
   JESSE JACKSON, reminding the Georgia Legislature of his Southern
roots: ``I am one of you. I worked hard to make the new South new _
now, let's make the new South better. I am my party's conscience.
By July, with your help, I want to be its candidate.''
   
   BOB DOLE, picking up an endorsement from former Texas Gov. John
Connally: ``I think today our campaign goes up another notch.''
</TEXT>
