<1ST_LINE>r w PM-GlassMerger     02-27 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Glass Merger,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Clears Way for Glass Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has given two of the
nation's largest manufacturers of glass containers the green light
to operate as a single company.
   On Friday, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia rejected a request by the federal government to block the
proposed merger between Owens-Illinois Inc. and Brockway Inc.
   Owens-Illinois spokesman John Hoff said the court denied a
motion by the Federal Trade Commission for an injunction and
dissolved a temporary stay of the proposed merger.
   Hoff said the court ruled that the FTC had failed to demonstrate
the need for an injunction.
   He said the company has extended its $60-per-share tender offer
for Brockway until 5 p.m. Monday, after which time it will be free
to proceed with the merger.
   Last week, U.S. District Court Judge Joyce Hens Green refused
the FTC's request for a preliminary injunction, ruling that the FTC
had not proven the deal would harm competition.
   The FTC then asked the appeals court to block the merger until
the agency could conduct an administrative review of potential
anti-competitive effects of the deal.
   Last September, the Toledo, Ohio-based Owens-Illinois proposed
to buy Brockway, of Jacksonville, Fla., for $750 million.
   The merger would make the combined company the largest
manufacturer of glass containers in the industry. The nation's top
manufacturer is Anchor Glass Container Corp., which controls 23.7
percent of the market.
   The FTC has said the merger might violate federal antitrust laws
by substantially reducing competition in the glass container
industry and creating conditions for price discrimination.
   But Judge Green accepted the argument by the two manufacturers
that competition from the plastics and metal-packaging industry
will keep down prices.
   Attorneys for Owens-Illinois say the purpose of the merger is to
achieve cost savings and efficiencies that will enable the combined
companies to vigorously compete against the producers of plastics,
metal and other types of packaging materials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880227-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 0300EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-IranianOil     02-27 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iranian Oil,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nader Group Says U.S. Imports of Iranian Oil Continued After Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Customs Service was unable to produce
immediate documentation that 6.4 million barrels of oil imported
from Iran late last year had been shipped or under contract before
a trade ban was imposed.
   Buyers Up, a consumer oil-buying cooperative affiliated with
consumer advocate Ralph Nader, said Friday the oil was imported in
November and December after President Reagan banned trade with that
country.
   The Customs Service said it believed the oil was legal, but
couldn't immediately lay its hands on the documents that would
prove itt.
   The oil accounted for 7.3 percent of U.S. crude imports for
those two months. The trade embargo took effect Nov. 29.
   Buyers Up director Jason Adkins said officials at the Foreign
Assets Control Division of the Treasury and the Strategic Branch of
the Customs Service ``were completely unaware of the November and
December shipments of Iranian oil to this country until we brought
it to their attention.''
   He agreed the oil could be legal, but said he had not been able
to find anyone in the government who could say it was.
   Customs Service spokesman David Hoover said, ``We're reasonably
sure _ we don't have the printout _ the oil was legal.'' He said it
might take two days to find the computer printout that would show
the certifications that the oil was exempt from the president's
action.
   Since the exemptions expired Dec. 31, Hoover said he would be
surprised if January statistics showed any shipments from Iran.
   Iran was a major supplier to the United States in the 1970s
before the revolution in that country, but shipments fell after the
1981 release of the American hostages seized in the U.S. Embassy in
Tehran.
   Iran generally accounted for from 1 percent to 3 percent of U.S.
crude imports in following years.
   Shipments rose sharply in the early months of 1987, however, and
in July Iran was the second largest supplier of crude to the United
States. Reagan said he imposed the ban to ensure that U.S.
purchases did not contribute to terrorism, which the U.S.
government says Iran supports.
   For all of 1987, Iran's crude shipments amounted to 5.1 percent
of U.S. crude imports, more than 88 million barrels worth $1.5
billion. That was more than triple the $468 million paid for 34
million barrels in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
