<1ST_LINE>u a AM-OfficerShot     02-27 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Officer Shot,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Off-Duty Policeman Slain During Robbery Attempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT ROTHSCHILD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An off-duty policeman was slain Friday during a
robbery attempt outside the grocery where he moonlighted as a
security guard, police said.
   A witness said the officer, Gary D. McCarthy, 32, was shot after
refusing to hand over a money bag. McCarthy, who was in street
clothes, died at Parkland Memorial Hospital four hours later, said
Police Chief Billy Prince.
   The 14-month member of the force was escorting the store manager
from a bank visit when a man jumped out of a car and attempted to
rob the manager, said Sgt. S.G. Shaw.
   `The officer went for his weapon and they got into a shootout,''
Shaw said.
   McCarthy was shot three times, and one of the bullets lodged in
his heart, hospital spokeswoman Paula Sears said. After the officer
fell to the ground, he fired twice at the fleeing vehicle and
shattered its rear window, police said.
   Officers found a car believed to be used in the robbery attempt
a few blocks away in a housing project, where witnesses said they
saw three men flee, police said. Helicopters searched for the men.
   Derick Johnson, 21, who was standing outside the store when the
shooting occurred, said the officer was carrying a money bag when
approached by the gunman.
   ``The guy tried to snatch the money, but the police officer
wouldn't give it to him,'' Johnson said. ``The guy was waving a
gun, and when the officer wouldn't give him the money, he just shot
him.''
   Two officers were slain last month in cases that sparked both
support for police and criticism from minorities who said officers
had been too trigger-happy when arresting blacks and Hispanics.
   A white officer was slain Jan. 23 by a deranged black vagrant
who had wrested the policeman's gun away on a downtown street. A
black officer was killed a week earlier during a suspected burglary
at an apartment complex where he worked off-duty.
   Prince, who earlier had charged that City Council criticism of
the Police Department had created so much public hostility that
police deaths were inevitable, said of Friday's shooting, ``I don't
see how you can make anything racial out of this.''
   The gunman was black; the officer white.
   ``The problem is we have too many people on the streets who
should be in the penitentiary,'' the chief said. ``There are too
many people on the streets who are mean.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
