<DOCNO> AP880227-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 0301EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p BC-MAINEAt-A-Glance     02-27 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-MAINE At-A-Glance,250</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are the methods for picking
delegates from Maine to attend the 1988 Democratic and Republican
national conventions this summer.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Method: Caucus
   Date: Sunday, February 28
   Presidential filing deadline: None.
   Pledged delegates: 23
   Super delegates: 4
   TOTAL: 27
   Delegates allocated: Sunday, February 28
   Selection of delegates: Saturday, May 14 and Sunday, May 15
   
   Maine uses a two-step caucus-convention system for picking its
delegates to the Democratic National Convention. Maine, which is
one of four states specifically allowed by Democratic Party rules
to begin the process of picking delegates before March 8, holds
local municipal caucuses on Feb. 28. The results of these caucuses
will govern the allocation of the state's 15 pledged national
convention delegates from congressional districts. Maine's
remaining eight pledged national convention delegates will be
chosen at the Democratic State Convention on May 13-15.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Method: Caucus
   Date: Sunday, February 28
   Presidential filing deadline: None.
   Delegates: 22
   Delegates allocated: Saturday, April 16
   Selection of delegates: Saturday, April 16
   Maine Republicans choose their national convention delegates
with town caucuses held between Feb. 26 and Feb. 28 to elect
delegates to the state convention and congressional district
conventions. Delegates are not required to pledge their support to
a presidential candidate. The state's two congressional district
conventions meet in conjunction with the state convention April
15-17. Six national convention delegates are chosen by the
congressional district conventions, and the remaining 16 delegates
are elected at-large by the state convention.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880227-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 0303EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Gephardt-Eastern     02-27 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gephardt-Eastern,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Accuses Gephardt of Playing `Cheap Political Games'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN WINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Eastern Airlines spokesman says Democratic
presidential candidate Richard Gephardt was playing ``cheap
political games'' when he criticized the attitude of company
management.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell described Gephardt's comments as
``a cheap attempt to get votes in the upcoming presidential
primaries.''
   Gephardt said controversy surrounding the Miami-based airline is
a national issue as well as a local one.
   ``What it signifies is an attitude in corporate America that the
way of the future is to cut jobs, is to engage in mergers, is to
engage in taking the important parts of the corporation out and
splitting them out into entities so that there can be quick paper
profits,'' Gephardt said.
   Reps. Larry Smith and Claude Pepper said they'll ask Congress to
hold hearings to investigate Eastern. The two Florida Democrats
support Gephardt's candidacy and appeared with him at a news
conference Friday.
   Gephardt, whose campaign has stressed a need to improve
corporate productivity, stopped short of calling for re-regulation
of the airline industry by the federal government. But the Missouri
congressman said if he's elected president, his administration will
enforce the industry's safety standards and change the way
management thinks.
   ``We will stop the attitude that the way to make profits is to
take them out of the hides of employees,'' said Gephardt, who met
with Eastern employees before the news conference.
   Eastern, which reported a net loss of $181.1 million in 1987, is
demanding contract concessions totaling $450 million from unions
representing its machinists, pilots and flight attendants.
   ``Eastern is trying to negotiate a sensible solution with the
(International Association of Machinists) to what has been a
long-term cost problem,'' Matell said. ``No company can pay baggage
handlers an average of $43,000 a year. We are doing everything
possible to negotiate a sensible solution with the IAM to solve the
cost problem.
   ``The irresponsible charges made today are not in the best
interest of any of the parties, least of all Eastern or its very
fine group of employees.
   ``It's extremely unfortunate that a collective bargaining
situation is being used for cheap political games.''
   Rep. Smith said many in Congress want to investigate Eastern
``to prevent further deterioration'' of the company. Pepper said
``there ought to be some way'' the breakup of Eastern can be
stopped.
   Gephardt supported the call for an investigation of Eastern.
   ``Congress should be concerned about the safety in this airline
and should be concerned about some of the actions that have been
taken,'' Gephardt said. He said recent management decisions at
Eastern reflect ``the dismantling of a great corporation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
