<HEAD>Two Soldiers Arrested For Alleged Mishandling of Secret Papers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARSTOW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two soldiers charged with mishandling
classified documents were arrested after a teen-ager who claimed to
be running drugs for one of them brought a briefcase of papers to a
TV station, officials said.
   The FBI arrested the two soldiers based at the Army's Fort Irwin
on Wednesday.
   James Weller, agent in charge of the FBI's Las Vegas office,
declined to say what the secret papers contained. He said
investigators were trying to determine whether the documents were
to be sold, and if so, to whom.
   A tip to a Las Vegas TV station from a former mental patient
prompted the arrests, Weller said.
   ``A young man came to our studios ... with a briefcase full of
secret documents,'' said Lynn Mathis, a reporter for station KTNV.
``He told us that he was employed by an Army sergeant as a drug
runner.''
   Station news director Steve Minium said the claimed he was tired
of dealing drugs and ``flipped out'' when he found the documents.
Minium declined to identify the 19-year-old.
   Staff Sgt. Edmund Washington Tuck, 24, and Specialist 4th Class
Kelly Joe Schmidt, 23, were arrested and held in the stockade at
Fort Irwin on charges of improper handling of classified documents,
Weller said.
   The informant told Minium he met Tuck in the mental ward of a
Victorville hospital and later moved in with him in Barstow. There
he said his job was to run a methamphetamine and LSD trafficking
operation for Tuck, Minium said.
   Agents are investigating the drug-trafficking allegations.
   Fort Irwin is in the Mojave Desert, about 140 miles northeast of
downtown Los Angeles. The Army trains soldiers in desert warfare
tactics at the base.
</TEXT>
