<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Soviet-Gulf     02-27 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Soviet-Gulf,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US May Accept Delay on Iran Arms Embargo If Soviets Agree to Early
UN Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is willing to talk about
delaying the effective date of an arms embargo against Iran in
exchange for Soviet agreement to have the United Nations vote on
the issue as soon as possible, a State Department official says.
   The State Department official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said Friday the proposal is designed to get a speedy
vote on the resolution while meeting the Kremlin's stated desire
for another round of diplomacy aimed at winning a cease-fire in the
Iran-Iraq war.
   The official said U.S. officials proposed Thursday to Soviet
representatives at the United Nations that the United States would
be willing to discuss delaying implementation of an embargo from 30
to 60 days.
   The United States has been pushing the Soviets to agree to the
embargo but the Soviets have been reluctant to implement one
without another diplomatic attempt by U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar to get Iran to agree to a cease-fire in its
seven-year war with Iraq.
   The Soviet position has been that any embargo should immediately
follow passage of an embargo resolution by the U.N. Security
Council, and therefore such a vote should be delayed to allow time
for more diplomatic efforts.
   Meanwhile, the Minneapolis Star & Tribune in today's editions
quoted administration officials who said the United States also is
willing to discuss with the Soviets the creation of a U.N. fleet to
stop and search ships suspected of carrying arms to Iran.
   The officials, who were not identified by the newspaper, said
the U.N. fleet would not be similar to a Soviet proposal that U.S.,
French, British and other Western naval forces in the Persian Gulf
be put under the U.N. flag and command.
   Rather, the arms-monitoring fleet under the U.S. proposal would
be made up of ships from neutral countries and would intercept
freighters at the mouth of the Gulf as they headed for the Iranian
port of Bandar Abbas, the newspaper said.
   The State Department official told The Associated Press that the
U.S. position all along has been to discuss proposals that might be
used to implement the embargo after passage of the U.N. resolution.
   The United States has not yet made a specific proposal to the
Soviets about how the embargo would be enforced, the official said.
   The Security Council adopted a resolution July 20 demanding an
immediate cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war, troop withdrawal,
prisoner exchange and enforcement steps if either party did not
comply.
   Only Iraq has agreed to the cease-fire. An attempt by the
secretary-general to bring both sides to agreement foundered in
September.
   Any of the five permanent members of the Security Council _ the
United States, the Soviet Union, Great Britain, France and China _
could veto an embargo resolution.
   The Soviet Union and other nations seeking better relations with
Iran have been reluctant to push for punitive enforcement.
   Earlier this month, U.S. officials said that China, which they
said sold $1 billion worth of arms to Iran last year, is not
expected to block an embargo.
</TEXT>
