<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Michael Jackson ordered more
flowers than other celebrities who've stayed at the Pensacola
Hilton, including Elizabeth Taylor and Bob Hope, and some of the
blooms went for vegetarian meals, workers said.
   ``When Michael left, I went up to the Presidential Suite to
collect the vases and they were everywhere, everywhere,'' said
Gehrig Galloway, owner of Gehrig's flower shop at the Hilton.
   ``I walked into the kitchen once when Damien was cooking,'' said
Thaisa Betts-Hester, the hotel's room division manager, referring
to the chef Jackson brought from Los Angeles. ``Damien was cooking
with an odd-looking flower with brown petals that he kept in a
Zip-loc bag. I asked him what was in the bag and he said,
`flowers.'''
   Jackson also ordered 32 cases of Evian mineral water for
drinking and bathing, baby corn, fresh herbs and sun-dried tomatoes
from Orlando, hotel employees said.
   He had a portable dance floor installed in his suite's living
room and was a polite guest, although one night he sprayed a can of
purple, gooey substance down a hallway, said Kathy Dyson, the
hotel's executive housekeeper.
   Jackson stayed at the hotel for two weeks as he rehearsed for
his national concert tour, which began this week in Kansas City, Mo.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Merrick, the impresario behind some of
Broadway's biggest hits, is returning to theater production in
London in May with an Australian comedy, ``Emerald City.''
   The play by David Williamson, who also wrote ``Sons of Cain,''
opens May 9 at Lyric Theater, Merrick's publicists announced Friday.
   It will be Merrick's second production in London, where his
long-running musical ``42nd Street'' opened in 1984.
   Merrick plans to bring ``Emerald City,'' a comedy about domestic
rivalry that he first saw last November at the Sydney Opera House,
to London with its Australian cast intact.
   Merrick's last Broadway production, a 1986 revival of Joe
Orton's ``Loot,'' was a financial failure but a critical success.
Among the biggest hits of his New York career were the musicals
``Gypsy'' and ``Hello, Dolly'' and Woody Allen's comedy ``Play It
Again Sam.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Barbra Streisand was named
female star of the decade at ShoWest '88, the annual trade show for
movie theater owners.
   Sean Connery was named male star of the year, and Shelley Long
female comedy star of the year. Mark Harmon was honored as most
promising new male star of the year and Anne Archer most promising
female new star of the year.
   ``Fatal Attraction'' director Adrian Lyne was named director of
the year. Don Simpson and Jerry Bruckheimer were named producers of
the year.
   The recipients were honored Thursday night at a banquet
concluding the three-day convention at Bally's Hotel.
   Streisand most recently appeared in the movie ``Nuts'' with
Richard Dreyfuss.
   Connery was nominated for an Oscar for his performance in ``The
Untouchables,'' and stars with Harmon in an upcoming film, ``The
Presidio.''
   Long is best known as Diane the barmaid from the TV comedy
``Cheers.''
   Archer was nominated for an Oscar for her performance in ``Fatal
Attraction.''
