<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Johnny Cash has agreed to appear
in a public service announcement to raise money for members of the
disbanded Nashville Symphony, say members of a group called Save
Our Symphony.
   Mike Karr, a symphony musician and member of a task force
examining ways to revive the deficit-ridden symphony, said the
players are excited about the fund-raising effort.
   ``We're excited that it has happened. It seems especially
encouraging that someone like Johnny Cash has agreed to take
part,'' Karr said Friday.
   The country singer's script says ``symphony music in Music City
is in serious trouble,'' and asks for donations to a Save Our
Symphony account to help ``keep the music from fading.''
   The money will be used to help out-of-work orchestra players put
on concerts or, if the symphony's board of directors decides to
stage concerts, will be donated to the Nashville Symphony
Association, said Connie Lincoln, an SOS committee member.
