<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Husker Du, a critically acclaimed underground
band whose latest album, ``Warehouse: Songs and Stories,'' was
released by Warner Bros. last year, has split up.
   Guitarist-songwriter Bob Mould this week confirmed the breakup
and called it ``more amicable than acrimonious.''
   Drummer Grant Hart said the split was ``not amicable at all.''
He said he left the trio on Dec. 15, a few days after the group's
last performance.
   ``I found it (Husker Du) less fun than other musical projects. I
couldn't do both Husker Du and other things because of dictums from
the other two members,'' Hart said.
   Bassist Greg Norton was the third member of Husker Du
(pronounced HOO-sker DOO), which was formed in 1978 as a punk-rock
outlet. Among the group's albums were ``Zen Arcade'' and ``New Day
Rising.''
