<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EDBRemembered Bjt   02-27 0670</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-EDB Remembered, Bjt,0688</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pesticide That Caused Cancer Scare Nears End Of The Line</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Remember EDB? Four years after the grain fumigant
was banned as a possible cancer risk amid panic over contaminated
popcorn, breakfast cereal and muffin mix, the public has nearly
forgotten it.
   Judy Heckman, chief of pesticide disposal for the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency, hasn't. Heckman plans to fly to
Texas to preside at the burning of the last 330,000 gallons of the
pesticide early next week.
   The EDB, or ethylene dibromide, to be incinerated was taken from
a warehouse and put on a train in Liberty, Mo., that left last week
for an industrial park in Deer Park outside Houston. More trains
will leave with the remaining gallons every Monday until June,
officials said.
   The federal government paid $2.5 million for what was left of
the chemical and may spend up to $8 million to get rid of it, EPA
officials estimate.
   It is the costly end of a story of national panic that erupted
after EDB was discovered in groundwater in Florida, Georgia,
California and Hawaii in 1983. Worried about its potential to cause
cancer, the EPA in September 1983 banned the use of EDB as a
pesticide for spraying on the ground.
   It was not until Feb. 3, 1984, however, that EDB was banned as a
fumigant for stored grain and limits were set on amounts in foods.
   Although the extent of the cancer risk remains uncertain, EDB
was banned amid a public outcry that the government was dragging
its feet.
   Calls poured in to poison control centers across the country
with worried questions about EDB.
   Massachusetts authorities ordered tainted baby foods tossed out,
and Florida's agriculture department had scores of products swept
from grocery store shelves.
   Pillsbury Co. alone claimed it lost $70 million as a result of
what U.S. Agriculture Secretary John Block referred to at the time
as ``some hysteria out there that really isn't warranted.''
   ``At the time it was a major environmental catastrophe and now
nobody's heard of it,'' said Rick Johnson, the EPA official who
headed the federal effort to investigate and eventually ban EDB.
``So we must have done something right.''
   EDB had been widely used on farms and in storage silos since
1948. It was used mainly to kill fungus on stored grains, but also
was sprayed on citrus fruits to kill fruit flies and on soil before
crops were planted.
   Scientists continued to give it their blessings through the
1950s when they were unable to detect any residue after the
chemical evaporated. But when more sensitive detection techniques
were developed, they revealed that minute traces of EDB were
clinging to the wheat and other grains all the way to the
supermarket.
   In 1975, the National Cancer Institute said the pesticide was
suspected of causing cancer in laboratory animals.
   By 1980 the EPA proposed to ban it after studies found the
health risks of cancer, genetic damage and reproductive disorders
outweighed its economic benefits.
   Johnson said such a risk assessment makes sense for the
government, but can be hard to put into perspective for the public.
   ``The difficult thing is to explain a very complicated science
and policy issue to a naive public,'' he said. ```Can I eat this
muffin mix?' Of course you can eat it.''
   Others see EDB as a case study in government overreaction.
   Stephen Klaidman of the Institute for Health Policy Analysis at
Georgetown University in Washington is including a chapter on EDB
in a book he is writing about the influence of the media on public
policy.
   ``The central question is whether the stuff was taken off the
market too quickly before they knew what (pesticides) they were
replacing it with (and) whether there was a panic reaction to a
chemical that was in the food chain for 30 years,'' Klaidman said.
``As far as I know, nobody has been able to connect a single death
to EDB from ingesting it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880227-0025 </DOCNO>
