<HEAD>Two-Day Sentence For Riding Motorized Skateboard Without License</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENNEWICK, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was sentenced to two days in jail
and fined $45 for riding a motorized skateboard without a driver's
license.
   Damian Vincent Ghiardi, 21, of Richland was convicted Tuesday of
driving with a revoked license and negligent driving. He ran a stop
sign in November on a skateboard powered by a chainsaw motor and
was knocked unconscious by a car.
   Defense attorney Nathan Kirk had argued that the skateboard was
not a motor vehicle because Ghiardi had to push it a block with his
foot to get up speed, but Benton County District Judge Eugene Pratt
disagreed.
   Prosecutor Bob Swisher said the case was treated seriously
because of the potential for more serious injury.
   Ghiardi's driver's license had been revoked last year when he
was convicted of attempting to elude a police officer, court
records show.
</TEXT>
