<HEAD>Cuomo The Non-Candidate Heads South</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, insisting he
doesn't want to play the role of presidential candidate or
kingmaker if there's a brokered national convention, headed for
North Carolina today to help a fellow Democrat.
   Against the backdrop of brokered convention talk, Cuomo was to
appear twice over the next several days in an area of the nation
that could be very important to Democrats come November.
   Tonight, Cuomo was to be in Raleigh, N.C., as the featured
speaker at a fund-raising event for Sen. Terry Sanford. On Tuesday,
Cuomo is to be in San Antonio, Texas, for an address at Trinity
University.
   Was it coincidence that Cuomo was heading south just before the
crucial March 8 Super Tuesday primaries?
   ``Oh no, that's a plan,'' joked Cuomo on Friday. ``You see, I'm
going to be March 1 in Texas and if it really goes well, then March
2 I'm going to announce I'm running.''
   The New York governor, the most prominent of the Democratic
non-candidates, said Friday that he still didn't believe there
would be a deadlocked convention.
   ``I would have no role,'' Cuomo said of a possible brokered
convention. ``They (the announced candidates) would confine
themselves to people who were candidates and talk to one another.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pittsburgh Mayor Backs Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pittsburgh Mayor Richard Caliguiri has
endorsed Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis for the Democratic
nomination for president.
   ``As the only Democratic candidate for president who has ever
managed a large government, Mike Dukakis has balanced nine straight
budgets and cut taxes in four of the last five years while
transforming his state into one of the models of economic success
in America,'' Caliguiri said Friday.
   Allegheny County Commissioner Pete Flaherty and Erie Mayor Louis
Tullio were among other Pennsylvania Democrats who announced their
support for Dukakis on Friday.
</TEXT>
