<HEAD>Simon Campaign Without Money in Oklahoma</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The coordinator of Democrat Paul Simon's
presidential campaign in Oklahoma says she hasn't been paid in a
while, but the organization will continue to operate.
   Glo Henley says the Simon campaign is ``not going to be doing
anything that requires great supplies of money. We won't do a lot
of long-distance calling.''
   She said it's been awhile since she's seen a paycheck from the
campaign, but ``I would continue working for him whether I got paid
or not.''
   The Illinois senator has announced that he can't afford to
campaign in the 20 states scheduled for the March 8 Super Tuesday
presidential primary.
   Ms. Henley said she has not changed her assessment of Simon's
chances in Oklahoma, saying she still would be happy to see him
garner 15 percent of the vote.
