<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Opera     02-27 0705</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Opera,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cheers End Crisis Night At Covent Garden</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a typical operatic tale _ a crisis night
with a storybook ending at the Royal Opera, Covent Garden.
   The lead singer felt terrible but sang on bravely.
   The second lead singer had a triumph, although he had never sung
his role before when he was summoned to London at short notice.
   When the first-night revival of Giuseppe Verdi's ``A Masked
Ball'' ended Friday night, it was cheers from a grateful audience
and nine curtain calls for cast and conductor.
   The story went like this:
   Italian baritone Giorgio Zancanaro, who was booked for the
second lead, fell ill with an ear infection which upset his sense
of balance and prevented him from traveling.
   So Romanian Alexandru Agache, who had never even sung in a major
opera house in the West took over, learning the role in just over
two weeks.
   ``I think this is the start of a big international career for
him,'' said conductor Richard Armstrong.
   Spanish tenor Giacomo Aragall had a valiant night.
   He also had an ear infection _ and bronchitis. But he got on
with the job and sang well, wavering at times, but hanging in there
even with his voice breaking in the last act.
   ``What a night,'' said Sir John Tooley, just retired director at
Covent Garden, when he called at Agache's dressing-room to
congratulate him.
   ``The human voice tends to be a recurring crisis. It causes
opera house managements the most awful headaches,'' Tooley said.
   ``Opera is full of problems, some of which you can deal with
away from the public gaze. But opera is the voice and a voice
crisis means you have got the public out front and the whole
performance to worry about _ your crisis is very visible,'' Tooley
said.
   ``You were stunning,'' Tooley told Agache. ``You coped
brilliantly with the acting and the singing.''
   ``You are very kind,'' murmured the Romanian, a big man with a
black beard, dripping sweat after the biggest test of his life.
   ``Aragall had a big problem, but he said he felt all right and
went on with it, but he sang under extreme difficulties all
evening,'' Tooley said.
   Agache, 33, lives in Cluj, in the heart of Romania's
Transylvanian country. He has sung in Budapest, Dresden, East
Berlin, Japan, Yugoslavia and France, and was expecting to make his
debut later this year in a major Western opera house, La Scala in
Milan. But Covent Garden got in first.
   Agache auditioned at Covent Garden on Jan. 19 and sang some
Verdi arias.
   ``He was recognized as having outstanding potential as a Verdian
baritone. He absolutely thrilled me as a singer,'' Armstrong
recalled.
   Two days later, Agache was in Leghorn, Italy, when his agent in
Frankfurt telephoned to say London wanted him as the ``perfect
replacement'' for Zancanaro.
   ``I sang a minor role in `A Masked Ball' in my debut with Cluj
Opera, but I had to start learning the major role of Anckarstrom
for Covent Garden,'' Agache said.
   He joined the rehearsals in London Feb. 9.
   In the opera, Anckarstrom is the secretary and friend of King
Gustavus III of Sweden, sung by Aragall.
   The secretary, burning with jealousy after discovering his wife
and the king are in love, joins a group of conspirators and stabs
the king to death at a masked ball.
   In history, the king _ one of the great rulers of the 18th
century _ was assassinated in 1792 at a masquerade in the Stockholm
opera house. He was shot in the back by a former royal bodyguard
named Anckarstrom.
   The assassin had his pistol hand cut off before he was beheaded
and his body quartered. But Verdi spared opera lovers and ended
with the king dying, ordering his assassin's release and pardoning
the conspirators.
   ``It's a difficult role because you have to marry very dramatic
acting and a big vocal part,'' Agache said.
   ``But it's a wonderful role, one of the great baritone parts,
and a pleasure to sing,'' he added.
   Verdi and ``A Masked Ball'' are much loved in London, which has
a vibrant and wealthy Italian community. The house was crowded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
