<HEAD>Hawaii Lab To Receive Remains of 20 Possible U.S. Vietnam War Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon says the remains of what may be
20 American servicemen missing from the Vietnam War are to be
delivered to U.S. officials in Hanoi on Wednesday and then
transported to an Army identification laboratory in Hawai.
   The Pentagon announced Friday that the Vietnamese government had
agreed to repatriate the remains, which will be taken to the
Central Identification Laboratory in Honolulu for identification.
   It will be the fourth-largest such transfer since the end of the
war. The largest occurred in August 1985, when the Vietnamese
returned 26 remains at once.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Yeutter Says Foreign Piracy Of Patents Draining U.S. Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. trade official says the failure of
foreign governments to crack down on foreign piracy of U.S.
patents, trademarks and copyrights is a growing problem that
distorts interrnational trade.
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter said Friday that the
annual drain on U.S. companies because of ``inadequate protection
of intellectual property'' may run as high as $43 billion to $61
billion.
   ``The failure of our trading partners to provide effective
protection for intellectual property is a severe and growing
problem that distorts trade,'' Yeutter said at a news conference.
   The U.S. International Trade Commission released a report at the
news conference that said U.S. companies surveyed by the government
reported losses of $23.8 billion in foreign piracy. The ITC said
actual losses are much greater because not all companies filled out
questionaires on the subject.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Air Force To Study Sites For Rail-Based MX Missiles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force says it plans to hold special
meetings for residents living near 11 bases selected to handle
rail-mounted MX missiles in order to ``identify environmental
issues.''
   The service announced a year ago it had selected F.E. Warren Air
Force Base in Wyoming to become the main operating base for any
rail-mounted MX missiles and 10 other bases for consideration as
additional ``rail garrisons.''
   The service said Friday it had launched an environmental impact
study of the bases and that it would review a number of deployment
alternatives, including the fielding of 100 MX missiles on rail
cars instead of just 50 missiles.
   Besides F.E. Warren, the list includes Blytheville Air Force
Base, Ark.; Little Rock Air Force Base, Ark.; Whiteman Air Force
Base, Mo.; Barksdale Air Force Base, La.; Dyess Air Force Base,
Texas; Fairchild Air Force Base, Wash.; Grand Forks Air Force Base,
N.D.; Minot Air Force Base, N.D.; Malstrom Air Force Base, Mont.,
and Wurtsmith Air Force Base, Mich.
</TEXT>
