<HEAD>CIA Official With Iran-Contra Links Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fourth CIA official involved in the
Iran-Contra weapons deals is leaving the agency.
   Alan Fiers, who established a secret supply network for
Nicaragua's Contra rebels, has resigned effective March 4, Bill
Baker, the agency's spokesman, said Friday.
   Fiers, who plans to go into private business, was one of several
CIA officials involved in the Iran-Contra affair who was
reprimanded last year by CIA Director William Webster because of
his role and his failure to inform Congress about the activity.
   Despite that disciplinary action, Fiers had continued to handle
Central American matters and had briefed members of Congress as
part of the Reagan administration's efforts to win renewed military
aid for the Contras.
