<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama-LatinReax     02-27 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Latin Reax,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Except for Sandinistas, Latiin Repudiation Grows For Noriega</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most Latin American governments expressed
support for Eric Arturo Delvalle's failed attempt to fire military
strongman, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, which cost Delvalle the
presidency of Panama.
   Nicaragua and Cuba appeared alone among Latin American nations
in announcing their support for Noriega, whose backers in Panama's
National Assembly ousted Delvalle early Friday after he tried to
dismiss the general.
   Ending a three-day meeting in Cartagena, Colombia, the foreign
ministers of seven Latin American countries said they had suspended
Panama from their Group of Eight, a regional organization for
political and economic cooperation.
   The foreign ministers of Argentina, Brazil, Colombia, Mexico,
Peru, Uruguay and Venezuela said in a communique that the
suspension was ordered because participation in the group requires
``the clear operation of democratic institutions among members.''
   The communique said the suspension would last ``until a new
evaluation of the circumstances'' in Panama, where Noriega controls
the 15,000-man military and police as Defense Forces chief.
   In Managua, President Daniel Ortega on Friday pledged
``unconditional solidarity'' with Noriega, who was indicted on drug
trafficking charges in Florida earlier this month.
   Ortega said the general's problems began when ``the United
States government arrived and told Gen. Noriega: `Gen. Noriega, we
need you to support us in an invasion against the Nicaraguan
people' and Gen. Noriega and the Defense Forces of Panama said no.''
   Panama helped the leftist Sandinistas in their guerrilla war
against the Nicaraguan government of President Anastasio Somoza,
who was ousted in July 1979. Noriega, considered the real power
behind Panama's civilian government, was instrumental in the effort.
   In Havana, the Cuban foreign ministry issued a statement blaming
the situation on an alleged U.S. campaign aimed at extending U.S.
control of the Panama Canal, the Cuban news agency Prensa Latina
said in a dispatch monitored Friday in Mexico City.
   Under a 1977 treaty with the United States, Panama is to take
over the canal and its defense in 1999.
   In Washington, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
Friday that the United States was not considering military
intervention in Panama, where the U.S. Southern Command and its
10,000 troops are based.
   In a statement, the Venezuelan government expressed support for
Delvalle's dismissal order of Noriega and called on Panama's armed
forces to respect it.
   ``The Venezuelan government reaffirms its unequivocal position
on the respect that the military forces in Panama owe to the
civilian power, as dictated by Panama's Constitution,'' said the
brief communique issued in Caracas.
   In a brief statement, the Argentine government said Friday it
``would like to make publicly known its solidarity with President
Eric Delvalle.''
   El Salvador's vice president, Rodolfo Castillo Claramount,
called Delvalle's ouster ``nothing more than a simple and vulgar
coup d'etat carried out by a group of military gorillas headed by
Noriega.''
   Castillo Calamount told a news conference Friday that the
Salvadoran government ``is seriously considering the possibility of
suspending diplomatic relations with the new Panamanian
government.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
