<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Sikhs     02-27 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family of Seven, Hindu Policeman Slain by Sikh Extremists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRISTAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh extremists were suspected fo killing
a Hindu police investigator early today and seven members of a Sikh
family, police in Punjab state said.
   The Sikh family was murdered Friday night at their farmhouse in
the village of Talwandi Chamchuk, about 25 miles west of Amritsar,
by six Sikh men armed with automatic rifles, said Amritsar District
Chief of Police Izhar Alam.
   The United News of India news agency quoted unidentified police
sources as saying the family apparently refused to pay extortion
money to members of the Khalistan Liberation Force, one the of Sikh
underground separatist groups.
   Khalistan is what the extremists call the independent Sikh
homeland they have been fighting to establish in the northern
Indian state since 1982.
   The victims were identified as Pirana Singh, 55, his wife,
Surinder, 50, two sons and two daughters and a visiting relative.
   The Hindu police investigator, Jeewan Lal, was killed near the
town of Ludhiana, southeast of Amritsar, police said.
   The latest slayings raised to at least 304 the number of people
killed this year in attacks blamed on Sikh extremists. Nearly
two-thirds of the victims have been Sikhs.
   Last year, more than 1,000 people were killed in Punjab by the
militants.
   Sikhs, whose religion is an offshoot of Hinduism, claim they are
discriminated against by India's Hindu majority. Sikhs comprise
about 2 percent of India's 800 million population but are a
majority in Punjab.
</TEXT>
