<DOCNO> AP880227-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 0354EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soldiers-Cocaine     02-27 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soldiers-Cocaine,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fourth U.S. Soldier Charged In Probe Of Smuggling From Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIO GHIGLIOTTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities charged a fourth
American soldier with smuggling cocaine to the United States aboard
a U.S. military plane from Panama.
   Richard Mark Williams was charged Friday before U.S. Magistrate
Roberto Schmidt Monge in San Juan with smuggling, possession and
possession with intent to distribute 17 pounds of cocaine.
   He was brought from Panama to Puerto Rico on Friday, authorities
said. His age, rank and hometown were not given.
   Authorities said the cocaine was among 77 pounds confiscated
Jan. 30 during a U.S. Customs Service inspection of a U.S. Military
Air Command plane traveling from Howard Air Force Base in Panama to
the United States.
   The plane had stopped for refueling at the U.S. Roosevelt Roads
Naval Station in northwestern Puerto Rico, a U.S. commonwealth.
   Williams became the fifth person, four of whom are American
soldiers, to be arrested and charged after the cocaine was found on
the plane.
   If convicted, Williams could be sentenced to up to 40 years in
prison.
   Federal officials said they were seeking one other American,
stationed in Panama, in the same investigation.
   Information about the case was limited because indictments
against the suspects were sealed in U.S. District Court in San Juan.
   Williams was detained in Panama, escorted by military personnel
on a commercial flight and arrested by FBI and Drug Enforcement
Administration agents on arrival at Luis Munoz Marin International
Airport in San Juan, according to court sources who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Two other U.S. soldiers facing federal charges of possessing and
importing 17 pounds of cocaine on the Jan. 30 flight pleaded
innocent Thursday at their arraignment in the district court.
   The two, Darrin Taylor, 19, of Chicago, and Franklyn Milton
Browne, 19, of Far Rockaway, N.Y., were arrested Jan. 30 along with
another soldier, Bruce Morris Mack, 20, of Gary, Ind., and Rafael
A. Valladares, 29, a Panamanian, who officials said was carrying
false documents identifying him as a U.S. soldier.
   Valladares, a civilian, was dressed in a U.S. Army uniform and
had dogtags and Army travel orders when arrested.
   Valladares and Mack were working independently of the other two
suspects and of each other, according to Arthur Barnes, assistant
special agent in charge of the DEA office in San Juan.
   The San Juan Star, citing unidentified official sources,
reported Friday that one American had established drug contacts in
Panama shortly before or after being discharged from the Army and
the other had supplied members of a drug ring with bogus travel
orders and military identification papers.
   It quoted the sources as saying one of the men had established
contacts with Panama's military chief, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega,
who is under indictment in the United States on drug trafficking
charges.
   ``The authorities now think that the ring had been using
military aircraft for at least a year, making weekly trips to the
U.S. with the drugs,'' the Star reported.
   It said the ring used fake travel orders, and the men who would
transport the drugs would leave on Fridays from Howard Air Force
Base and travel to South Carolina and Texas, where the narcotics
were unloaded. The carriers would be back on the Howard base by
Monday, before they could be declared absent without leave, the
newspaper said.
</TEXT>
