<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 0423EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Deng-Biography     02-27 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deng-Biography,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Publishes Photo Biography of Deng</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior leader Deng Xiaoping, who has criticized
the personality cult that surrounded Mao Tse-tung, is the subject
of a government-published biography that includes 500 photographs
dating back to 1921.
   Among the pictures, half of which are being published for the
first time, are shots taken by Deng's daughter when Mao exiled Deng
to the countryside during the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution, the
official China Daily said today.
   Deng, 83, was branded a capitalist during the upheaval but came
back after Mao's death in 1976 to steer China on a course of
market-oriented reform and opening to the outside world that has
significantly improved living standards.
   The 304-page book, compiled by the official Xinhua News Agency
and the Communist Party's Department on Party Literature, was
described as the most complete and accurate introduction of Deng
printed in China.
   The book also contains wartime photos of Deng with his wife Zhou
Lin and pictures of him playing billiards and cards, swimming and
mountain climbing.
   More than 250 people, including Politburo Standing Committee
member Hu Qili, gathered at the Great Hall of the People Friday
evening to celebrate publication of the book, China Daily said.
   Deng, who has cut down his public appearances since retiring
from most of his top posts last fall, did not attend the party.
Although in semi-retirement, he is still regarded as China's most
powerful politician.
   The book has been published in Chinese and English, with French,
Japanese and German editions to come out later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
