<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Peasant     02-27 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Peasant,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airplane Bought By Chinese Peasant Languishes in Storage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The celebrated case of a wealthy Chinese
peasant who bought a cropduster for his village has become a tale
of woe with the revelation today that the plane never has been used
by the farmers.
   Guo Yuanying of central Henan province bought the ``Bee-3''
model ultralight aircraft for $7,258 in April 1984 to help
neighbors in spraying pesticides and fertilizer, China's domestic
China News Service reported.
   China's official Xinhua News Agency said at the time that Guo,
then 37, was the country's first peasant to buy an airplane,
drawing from his textile accessory factory's hefty profits.
   That report said the local government planned to send three
peasants to the Beijing Aeronautical Engineering institute to learn
to fly and would build a small airfield.
   But today's report said the local government did not have the
money and that the airplane remained at the Zhengzhou airport for
two years before being donated to a tourist resort near the Yellow
River, where it has languished in a warehouse.
   The domestic news service noted that Guo's village is in a
region plagued by locusts and asked, ``Why is it so difficult to
utilize modern technology?''
</TEXT>
