<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Swaggart-Prostitute     02-27 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Swaggart-Prostitute,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prostitute Says Drug Use Ruined Lie Detector Test</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents of 4th graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prostitute says drug use caused her to fail
a lie detector test when questioned about her relationship with
evangelist Jimmy Swaggart, a television station reported.
   Debra Murphree, who claims Swaggart paid her to pose nude, took
the polygraph test voluntarily Monday after offering to sell the
National Enquirer her story for $100,000, Paul Levy, a senior
editor of the supermarket tabloid, said Friday.
   Levy said the examiner, an expert with 15 years' experience with
the New York City Police Department, concluded the 28-year-old
woman was not truthful on six questions, including one in which she
denied making up the story.
   He said the story included claims that Swaggart paid her to
perform oral sex as well as pose naked and talk dirty.
   Levy said the Enquirer decided not to print her story based on
the lie detector results, her drug history and her record of having
been arrested in three states.
   WVUE-TV of New Orleans, which had interviewed Murphree and aired
her claims this week, reported Friday that she blamed the lie
detector failure on drugs.
   ``I was very nervous. I had been doing crack and cocaine just
the day before. I had trouble remembering some of the questions,''
the station quoted Murphree as saying.
   Murphree, who was said to be Bahamas-bound on Thursday, has
three children living with her parents in Indiana and has a record
of prostitution arrests in Florida, Tennessee and Louisiana,
authorities said.
   John Martinez, a companion of Murphree, told The Palm Beach Post
that Murphree visited Swaggart weekly for a year in New
Orleans-area motel rooms at $50 per meeting.
   Martinez acknowledged he has been trying to sell Murphree's
story since Swaggart's tearful public confession of sin Sunday,
which led the Assemblies of God denomination to recommend the
evangelist be suspended from preaching.
   Swaggart said he was guilty of sins against his wife and God,
but has not commented further. Associates of Swaggart have
described his misconduct as involving pornographic acts.
</TEXT>
