<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea     02-27 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea,0615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissidents Reject Amnesty, Protest In Seoul</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SEL3,4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said it freed more than
2,000 prisoners today as part of a ``grand amnesty.'' Opposition
leaders called the clemency deceitful, claiming 1,200 political
prisoners were still in jail.
   ``Release all prisoners of conscience,'' the National Coalition
for Democracy, the main coalition of dissident groups, said in a
statement.
   The new government of President Roh Tae-woo said it released
2,134 people from jails today and 5,100 others had their sentences
reduced or their civic rights restored.
   About 125 dissidents were among those freed and 1,606 others had
sentences reduced or regained their rights. The rest of the people
included in the amnesty were common criminals.
   Dissidents and other prisoners were released early today from
prisons in Seoul and other cities.
   Roh, who took office Thursday with a promise to introduce
sweeping democratic reforms, said the amnesty was to build public
confidence and underline the government's determination to end
decades of authoritarian rule.
   But the amnesty did not include dissidents who had refused to
repent or ``fundamentally reject free democracy,'' the government
said. Dissidents who had committed serious crimes such as murder or
arson were also excluded.
   Among the excluded were prominent dissident leaders Chang Ki-pyo
and Kim Kun-tae, both serving seven-year terms for inciting riots.
Amnesty International and other human rights groups have demanded
Kim's release.
   About 100 radicals and relatives of jailed dissidents staged a
protest today in Seoul outside the National Council of Churches
building. They shouted ``Release all the prisoners,'' but passersby
showed little interest.
   Scuffles, kicking and punching broke out as riot police barred
the way when the protesters tried to march. Furious protesters hit
police with placards and fists and seized several riot shields and
smashed them, but they were prevented from marching.
   Dissident leader Rev. Moon Ik-hwan, who had his civic rights
restored under the amnesty, told the protesters the amnesty was a
fraud. ``As long as there is a single dissident in jail, democracy
cannot be achieved,'' he declared.
   In announcing the ``grand amnesty'' Friday, Culture and
Information Minister Chung Han-mo said it was intended to promote
``national harmony and restore public confidence'' in the
government.
   At a news conference today, opposition leader Kim Dae-jung
called for ``total'' amnesty, complaining that the number of
political prisoners released constituted only a small portion of
political detainees. He called on the government to free all but
those who admitted to being communists.
   Communism is outlawed in South Korea.
   Kim Dae-jung later denounced Roh's government at a rally in
Seoul attended by about 4,000 people. He reiterated his claim that
presidential elections in December had been rigged, and urged
people to vote for the opposition in upcoming legislative elections.
   But the veteran opposition leader also said he was willing to
give Roh a chance to meet his promise to usher in full democracy.
   ``I can cooperate with Roh as the incumbent ruler in power if he
carries out sweeping reforms, including complete freedom, release
of all politicl prisoners and full guarantee of other civil
rights,'' he said.
   Kim Dae-jung and rival opposition leader Kim Young-sam were both
defeated by Roh in the presidential balloting, though the winner
did not receive a majority of the ballots cast.
   Government officials say 276 political detainees are still
behind bars _ 216 still awaiting trial and 60 others serving
sentences for serious crimes.
   The authorities hinted that some of those awaiting trial may be
freed when judicial processes are completed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
