<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CopKilled 1stLd-Writethru a0459 02-27 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cop Killed, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0459,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer Slain Guarding Home From Drug Dealers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 4th graf ``An attack'' to UPDATE with
additional reward and INSERTS two grafs after 7th graf pvs ``The
man'' to UPDATE with quote from homeowner. Picks up 8th graf pvs
``Ward dismissed.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The murder of a young policeman shot three times
in the head at point-blank range was intended to intimidate those
who help authorities in the war against drug dealers, the police
commissioner said.
   Officer Edward Byrne, 22, killed as he sat in his patrol car
early Friday, was guarding the home of a Queens man who complained
to authorities about neighborhood crack dealers, authorities said.
   Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward called it ``a deliberate
assassination'' and an ``attempt to intimidate not just that
witness but all'' who cooperate with police against drug dealers.
   ``An attack on a cop is an attack on society,'' said Mayor
Edward I. Koch, adding that the city was offering a $10,000 reward
for information leading to the arrest and conviction of the killer
or killers.
   A private group calling itself Citizens Outraged at Police Being
Shot and the Daily News offered an additional $10,000 each.
   A confidential, 24-hour hotline was established for tips. Police
said that one or more people had seen part of the attack, which
took place in a residential area beset with cocaine trafficking and
violence related to turf wars between drug dealers.
   Witnesses told police that two men pulled up to Byrne's cruiser
in a car. One got out, approached the patrol car, then quickly
fired five shots into the vehicle before fleeing with the other man.
   The man being protected had a firebomb thrown through his window
after he provided information that led to the arrest in November of
a young man suspected of dealing crack, authorities said. Two
others were arrested in connection with the firebombing, and two
more were arrested on charges stemming from threats made against
the homeowner.
   The 40-year-old man, a Guyanese immigrant who goes by the single
name Arjune, said Friday that he has moved his family from the
house, which he has been unsuccessfully trying to sell.
   ``I heard the shots. ... I can't say anything. ... I'm scared to
death, in fear for my life,'' he said Friday.
   Ward dismissed speculation that Friday's killing was related to
the sentencing Thursday of Lorenzo ``Fat Cat'' Nichols, the reputed
head of a drug empire in southeast Queens.
   Nichols, 29, was sentenced to prison for 25 years to life for 11
narcotics and gun convictions.
   Police in recent years have tried to respond to the growing drug
trade in southeast Queens, launching a major drug sweep known as
``Operation Cleanup'' in September 1985. In its first two years, it
resulted in 400 felony drug arrests and 225 misdemeanor arrests,
along with seizure of 85 firearms and 30 pounds of cocaine.
   The slaying cast a pall over a promotion ceremony Friday for 91
people at Police Headquarters.
   ``Each of us enters this job with full knowledge of the inherent
danger, but we do not expect to be gunned down in this manner,''
Ward told the crowd.
   Byrne, whose father is a retired police lieutenant and whose
older brother is a federal prosecutor, was single and lived with
his parents in the Long Island city of Massapequa. He had been a
police officer less than two years.
</TEXT>
