<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-FreedomRun     02-27 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Freedom Run,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gandhi Joins Thousands in Run to Mark 40 Years of Independence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 120,000 people, from toddlers
to Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, ran in a patriotic show of strength
today to mark the 40th year of India's independence.
   Gandhi, dressed in a gray track suit and sneakers, flagged off
the ``Freedom Run'' near Parliament House, and thousands of people,
mainly schoolchildren, flooded the roads.
   Most of the runners wore T-shirts of saffron, green and white,
the colors of the Indian flag.
   Gandhi and about 70 other VIPs, including Cabinet ministers and
movie stars, joined the run for awhile. The prime minister was
surrounded by a human wall of security guards.
   He ran for about a half a mile before being whisked away in his
bulletproof car. Gandhi faces death threats from Sikh extremists
who have waged a campaign for an independent nation in India's
northern Punjab state.
   Thousands of policemen dotted the entire route of the 24-mile
run through the city, which ended at the National Stadium.
   The event was organized to mark 40 years since India gained its
independence from British colonial rule on Aug. 15, 1947.
</TEXT>
