<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-News Strike,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Journalists Go On Nationwide Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian journalists today began a nationwide strike
intended to prevent publication of daily newspapers on Sunday and
Monday.
   The walkout, called to protest a breakdown in negotiations for a
new contract, will extend to radio and television journalists
Sunday and Monday.
   Transmitters of the nation's main news agencies, ANSA and AGI,
went silent at 7 a.m.
   The strike will rob readers of news of Italy's Olympic skiing
hero Alberto Tomba, who was going for a second gold medal. However,
the race was being broadcast live on three channels.
   The strike is the latest in a series of job actions by
journalists. The journalists, whose contracts expired in Decmeber,
are seeking pay increases and control over new technology.
   In a related development, the price for daily newspapers is
being raised 8 cents to 72 cents beginning next Tuesday.
   Italians also faced other strikes this weekend.
   Airport ground personnel scheduled a 24-hour walkout Sunday in a
continuing contract dispute, causing the state-run Alitalia
Airlines to cancel many flights to and from Rome's Leonardo da
Vinci airport. The airline said intercontinental flights would
operate on schedule.
   Many schools across Italy, which are normally open Saturday
morning, were shut down as a result of a strike by teachers
demanding higher pay and better working conditions.
</TEXT>
