<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Mideast, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0499,0666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Meets Syrian Leader After Plan Rebuffed In Jordan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 11th graf, `After the ...,' to UPDATE
with PLO statement released in Amman. PICKS up 12th graf, `Shultz
pushed ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz took
his Middle East peace plan to Syria today after Jordan rebuffed his
attempt to exclude the Soviet Union and the PLO from Middle East
peace negotiations.
   ``Obviously that's their point of view,'' Shultz said in Amman
after hearing Jordanian demands sharply at odds with U.S. and
Israeli positions.
   Shultz has called for Palestinian participation in negotiations,
but not participation by the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Shultz also opposes an active role for the Soviets in shaping a
Middle East settlement to end the Arab-Israeli dispute.
   But Jordanian Foreign Minister Taher Masri, while calling
Shultz's meeting with Jordanian officials ``serious and useful,''
said the only way for a peace settlement was through an
international conference, including the Soviets and the PLO.
   In Israel, Shultz also encountered resistance from Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir to his plea for an accelerated timetable
for negotiations leading to talks on a final settlement by December.
   Israeli sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Shamir
urged Shultz to move slowly on the issue of Palestinian self-rule
despite the 11 weeks of anti-occupation unrest.
   The U.S. plan calls for immediate talks on Palestinian self-rule
and negotiations by December on the final status of the West Bank
and Gaza Strip, which Israel seized from Egypt and Jordan in the
1967 Middle East war.
   Shultz had hoped with his mission to diffuse unrest on the
occupied territories, where Palestinians have clashed with Israeli
soldiers almost daily since since Dec. 8.
   A further setback was a boycott Friday in Jerusalem by 15
Palestinians invited by Shultz to discuss their aspirations for
national rights.
   After the boycott, Shultz read a statement carried on Israeli
television to Arabs in the region saying, ``opportunity knocks
loudly on your door. Now is the time to get to work.''
   In Amman, the PLO said today it is willing to meet U.S.
officials ``on any level,'' and said American rejection of a
meeting shows the United States is not serious about Arab-Israeli
peace.
   U.S. policy forbids American diplomats to meet ranking PLO
officials because the the administration regards the PLO as a
terrorist organization.
   Shultz pushed on and flew to Damascus to discuss the gloomy
outlook with Syrian President Hafez Assad, whom he has described as
a key player in any Middle East settlement.
   Shultz is the first U.S. secretary of state to visit Damascus
since 1983.
   In Amman, Masri said the permanent members of the U.N. Security
Council _ the United States, the Soviet Union, China, Britain and
France _ and the PLO must be invited to peace talks.
   Israel refuses to deal with the PLO, which is waging a guerrilla
war against the Jewish state, and Israel has U.S. backing for this
position.
   Shultz also supports Shamir in trying to keep the Soviets from
trying to influence the outcome of any peace talks.
   In Jerusalem, U.S. diplomats tried again to arrange a meeting
between Shultz and Palestinian figures.
   In his television statement Friday, Shultz implied the
Palestinians were afraid to meet him because they would be defying
the PLO, which instructed Palestinians in the occupied territories
to boycott Shultz's invitation.
   ``Peace-making is difficult,'' Shultz said. ``Peace has its
enemies, but peace is a necessary ingredient to a decent life.''
   The stopover in Amman was not considered critical, since King
Hussein is in London, where he will meet with Shultz on Tuesday.
   On Sunday, Shultz meets again with Shamir and Foreign Minister
Shimon Peres before leaving for Cairo to see Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak.
   Shultz returns to Jerusalem again Sunday night for further talks
with Shamir.
</TEXT>
