<HEAD>US Soldiers Arrive For Major Military Exercises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Navy ship docked in the
southern port city of Pusan on Saturday and discharged the first
U.S. soldiers and equipment to arrive for large military exercises,
news reports said.
   The Yonhap news agency said the 26,000-ton Regulus arrived from
Takoma, Wash., carrying 714 U.S. soldiers, 14 helicopters, three
tractors and 1,036 trucks.
   The United States and South Korea plan to deploy about 200,000
soldiers in the annual ``Team Spirit'' exercises, scheduled to run
from late February to early May.
   U.S. officials said the exercises this year will involve about
60,000 U.S. military personnel along with U.S. and South Korean
jets, a U.S. aircraft carrier and escorting warships.
   About 40,000 U.S. troops from bases in the Pacific and the
United States are to be brought in to join American troops based in
South Korea.
   North Korea has strongly opposed the exercises.
</TEXT>
