<HEAD>Rebels Claim Sinking of Six Mozambican Naval Vessels</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Lake Nyassa and Niassa province are cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mozambican rebels sank six military
patrol boats on Lake Nyassa in northwestern Mozambique after
killing dozens of soldiers elsewhere in the country, the rebels
said Saturday.
   The Mozambican National Resistance said in a statement
distributed in Lisbon that it sank the boats Feb. 20 at the
Metangula base on the eastern shore of Lake Nyassa, which borders
Mozambique, Malawi and Tanzania.
   The statement said the attack put a company of 100 Mozambican
marines out of action, but it did not mention casualties. Rebel
spokesmen could not be contacted for comment Saturday.
   Guerrillas also captured three towns in northeastern Niassa
province Feb. 22 and 23, the statement said. It gave no further
details.
   The right-wing rebels, also known as RENAMO, have been fighting
since 1977 to topple Mozambique's Marxist government. South Africa
denies Mozambican charges it supports the group.
   The rebels also said they killed several Cuban and Soviet
advisers and captured 43 Mozambican soldiers Feb. 17 in an attack
on the town of Bela Vista, 30 miles south of the capital, Maputo.
   On the day same, the rebels claimed they occupied the town of
Lugela in central Zambezia province, killing 18 Mozambican troops
and 17 Tanzanian soldiers fighting for the government.
   There was no independent confirmation of the claims nor any
indication of rebel casualties.
</TEXT>
