<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Ban, Bjt,0930</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa's Largest Anti-Apartheid Group Faces Survival Fight</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Since mid-1985, top leaders of
the United Democratic Front have been facing treason charges in a
trial viewed as a likely prelude to a ban on the nationwide
anti-apartheid coalition.
   Last week, the government decided not to wait for a verdict.
   It banned all the group's activities and imposed severe
restrictions on the few coalition leaders still free. Most of the
18 groups banned from political activity last week were affiliated
with the front.
   The apparent goal of the ban was to stamp out a grass-roots
movement that in less than five years had become the largest _ and
in many ways the most potent _ opposition group in South Africa's
history.
   The United Democratic Front has proved resilient before, and it
may survive this latest blow. Even if it does not, its legacy seems
assured.
   ``The (coalition) was the most effective political force that
has operated in black townships ever,'' said Tom Lodge, a political
scientist at Johannesburg's University of the Witwatersrand.
   The activist spirit fostered by the group ``will continue under
different forms and will always present a challenge to the
government,'' Lodge said.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a segregated society in
which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5
million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts,
schools and health services.
   Before Aug. 20, 1983, when the United Democratic Front was
launched at rally near Cape Town, South Africa had never
experienced anything like the coalition.
   It represented the first attempt to meld local and regional
anti-apartheid groups into a single network. It pledged itself both
to militance and to non-violence.
   And though it has always been predominantly black, it welcomed
white and Asian members who embraced its ideals.
   The coalition grew to encompass more than 600 organizations with
about 2 million members. The affiliates include church, civic,
educational and youth groups extending into virtually every black
township in the country.
   Its original goal was to oppose formation of the tricameral
Parliament, which has chambers for whites, Asians and people of
mixed-race but excludes the black majority. It backed a boycott of
the 1984 elections for the Asian and mixed-race chambers,
contributing to turnouts of less than 30 percent.
   Since then, coalition affiliates have waged a variety of
campaigns, ranging from prolonged rent boycotts to advocacy of
greater black control over education.
   Some analysts say the group's most impressive achievement has
been psychological _ convincing ordinary people that it was worth
organizing to build unified opposition to apartheid.
   The Rev. Allan Boesak, a prominent activist who helped found the
coalition, said after learning of Wednesday's crackdown that the
group's day-to-day operations were less important that its
symbolism to blacks.
   ``It's a living sign that our of belief that the days of white
dominance are over,'' he said. ``That's something you cannot ban.''
   Twice, the government has charged groups of prominent United
Democratic Front officials with treason in an effort to prove that
the coalition conspired with the outlawed African National Congress
guerrilla movement to provoke violence and make South Africa
``ungovernable.''
   One group, including co-presidents Archie Gumede and Albertina
Sisulu, went free after the case against them collapsed for lack of
evidence.
   But three other officials, including its national secretary and
its chief spokesman, have been held since 1985 during the country's
longest-running political trial. They and 16 co-defendants who are
free on bail dispute government charges that the organization
instigated the black unrest that broke out in September 1984 and
claimed some 2,500 lives over the next three years.
   Many activists had predicted that a guilty verdict at the
treason trial would be followed by a ban on the coalition.
   The trials have been only one of several tactics used by the
government to weaken the coalition, which in many instances has
been forced to operate clandestinely. Virtually all of its national
executive committee members have been detained or gone into hiding
during the 20-month-old state of emergency, and the few who
remained in the open were issued banning orders last week barring
them from United Democratic Front activity.
   According to monitoring groups, about 75 percent of the
estimated 30,000 people detained for varying periods during the
emergency belonged to the coalition's affiliates.
   The government has accused the group of contributing to a
``revolutionary climate'' in which its followers rejected
established institutions and harassed or killed blacks linked to
the white authorities.
   Gumede, in recent interviews, acknowledged that some coalition
followers had resorted to coercion and said the government's
restrictions on the group's leaders made it difficult to instill
discipline.
   ``We are on the run,'' he told Leadership magazine late last
year. ``Sooner or later, we are going to find ourselves in a real
jam, because people do not have sufficient time to think.''
   Gumede is now banned from giving interviews or speaking
publicly. His co-president, Mrs. Sisulu, is under police orders to
stay in her home between 6 p.m. and 5 p.m.
   As they learned of the restrictions, an unsigned coalition
statement was distributed to the news media.
   Its closing message: ``Nothing, we repeat nothing, will stand in
the way of the United Democratic Front as it carries out its
historical task and duty of uniting the oppressed and silenced
people of our country.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
