<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebel Violence Leaves 11 Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist rebels ambushed a military
jeep Saturday, killing two soldiers and bringing to 11 the number
of people killed in two days of scattered clashes, the military
said.
   Rebels also stormed a hospital in the northern Luzon province of
Cagayan and carted off medicine, food and other supplies, military
officials said. One civilian was wounded in the raid.
   The government-run Philippine News Agency said an undetermined
number of New People's Army guerillas opened fire on a military
jeep on the central island of Bohol. A constabularly captain was
wounded in addition to the two fatalities.
   In another report, the military said three communist rebels and
six Moslem guerrillas were killed in earlier clashes in Cagayan and
on the southern island of Mindanao.
   Maj. V.G. Jalligao said at least 50 New People's Army guerrillas
stormed the Matilde Olivas Hospital late Wednesday in Cagayan
province. Jalligao said one civilian was wounded in the raid, after
which the rebels fled toward a mountain village with medicine, food
and other supplies.
   In Mindanao's Lanao del Sur province, troops from the army's
35th Infantry Battalion came upon 20 Moslem rebels of the Moro
National Liberation Front during a patrol Friday and killed six of
them in the ensuing gun battle. The remaining rebels fled, the
military said.
   The clash occurred on the day President Corazon Aquino traveled
to Mindanao and the largely Moslem island province of Tawi-Tawi to
unveil economic development programs.
   During a speech in Zamboanga City, Mrs. Aquino warned Moslem
countries against encouraging violence by the Moslem rebel group,
which has been waging a 16-year insurgency for a separate state in
the south.
   Fighting in the Moslem insurgency peaked in the mid-1970s after
the war had claimed more than 50,000 lives.
