<2ND_LINE>AM-Smiling Shooter,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police: Woman Says She Shot Officer To Be Example</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who smiled while shooting
point-blank at a police officer who stopped to help her told
investigators she had been planning to shoot a police officer for
some time, authorities said.
   ``She decided this morning it was time to go ahead with it. She
figured she'd just drive around until she found one,'' police
spokesman Dee Anderson said.
   Pamela Diane Takhar, 33, was charged with attempted capital
murder and was being held in lieu of $250,000 bond, officer Lisa
Male said Saturday. Officer Gene Evans, 26, was wearing a
bulletproof vest and suffered no serious injuries in the Friday
morning shooting.
   ``The woman plainly told us she wanted to shoot a police
officer,'' said Anderson. ``She said that if she did kill a police
officer, she would go to jail. Then the whole world would know what
happens when you shoot someone.''
   Police said Evans stopped to investigate an apparently disabled
vehicle and found a woman sitting in the passenger side.
   ``He said she was very confused, and he had a conversation with
her that didn't make very much sense,'' Anderson said. ``She turned
around and smiled and then shot him.''
