<HEAD>Newspaper Says Plaza Hotel Could Be Converted To Co-op</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The elegant Plaza Hotel, the Fifth Avenue
bastion of luxury overlooking Central Park, might be sold within
weeks and a portion of it could be converted to cooperative
apartments, a newspaper reported Saturday.
   The 18-story hotel offers rooms from $195 a night for a single
to $800 for a suite.
   Real estate dealers Philip Pilevsky and Arthur G. Cohen said
they were close to a $400 million to $500 million agreement to buy
the hotel, The New York Times reported.
   It said the two have formed a joint venture with the Mandarin
Oriental Hotel Group of Hong Kong, which owns luxury hotels on both
sides of the Pacific, to buy the Plaza from the Bass family of Fort
Worth, Texas.
   Pilevsky said the style and spirit of the hotel would remain,
but part of it would be converted to cooperative ownership after
renovations.
