<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--YoungSoldier     02-27 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Young Soldier,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retirement For `Youngest American Soldier Since Civil War'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT ORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who first joined the military when
he was just 13 has retired after more than 29 years of serivce.
   ``I'm proud. The Army's been my entire life, my home ... my
family,'' Master Sgt. Gilbert Zamora, 52, said at Friday's ceremony.
   The Army believes Zamora was the last Korean War combat veteran
still on active duty and the youngest American soldier since the
Civil War.
   According to Zamora's record, he lied about his age and joined
the California National Guard in 1949 at the age of 13.
   The Los Angeles teen-ager was ordered to active duty in 1951, at
the start of the Korean War. But his parents found out and told the
Army he was a juvenile.
   ``I was out of the Army in three hours,'' he said. ``It broke by
heart and I refused to go home at first.''
   He joined up again when he was 17 in 1953, in time to fight in
the Korean War's vicious battle of Pork Chop Hill.
</TEXT>
