<HEAD>Passenger Plane Crashes in Siberia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Aeroflot passenger plane crashed on landing
today at an airport in western Siberia, resulting in deaths and
injuries, the official Tass news agency said.
   Tass said the Tupolvev-134 airliner ``met with an accident while
landing'' at the city of Surgut, 1,400 miles east of Moscow. The
report did not say how many people were aboard, or how many had
been killed.
   ``Measures were being taken to rescue people. Necessary aid is
being given to the crash victims. There is loss of life,'' Tass
said in a three-paragraph report.
   ``The causes of the disaster are being investigated by a special
commission,'' it said.
   Domestic Aeroflot flights usually are filled to capacity.
Depending on the seating configuration, the Tu-134, which has twin
turbofan engines, can carry from 80 to 96 passengers, according to
Jane's All the World's Aircraft.
   Tass said the flight had originated in Minsk, with stops in
Kuibyshev and Tyumen, before a final scheduled landing in Surgut.
</TEXT>
