<2ND_LINE>PM-Maine GOP, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0441,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Campaign Gains, But Bush Forges Ahead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with today's turnout; picks up
2nd graf pvs, bgng: Statewide, the xxx</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCIS X. QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maine Republicans, attracted by an
energetic Pat Robertson challenge to part-time resident George
Bush, continued to turn out in heavy numbers today during the
party's first consolidated caucus weekend.
   In Augusta, more than 300 people gathered this morning for
Kennebec County caucuses. ``The level of interest is strong,'' said
Robertson campaign organizer Mark Finks. ``The enthusiasm
originates from my candidate. We're turning out in massive
numbers.''
   On Friday, Robertson won a tie in Portland and a clear-cut
victory in Caribou, but Bush's campaign appeared to add to its
commanding lead in state convention delegates.
   Statewide, the Bush campaign claimed Friday to have won 166 of
the first 234 slots awarded. Bush's count gave Robertson 28, Bob
Dole 20, and Jack Kemp 5, with 15 uncommitted.
   The delegates totaled by the Bush campaign included 137
previously elected in caucuses in 43 towns since late January. The
Republicans will select the rest of the 1,506 state delegates
during caucuses today and Sunday.
   Those delegates will gather at the state convention in Bangor in
April to select 22 delegates to the Republican National Convention.
   The results of the Republican caucuses do not bind state
convention delegates and party leaders are not compiling the local
tallies immediately.
   In Portland on Friday night, supporters of Bush and Robertson
battled raucously over voting rules until Robertson backers, aided
by a small faction for Dole, voted to force the caucus to scrap its
winner-take-all standard for awarding delegate slots.
   In the presidential preference poll that followed, Robertson
drew 130 votes, Bush 127, and Dole 30. Bush and Robertson each were
awarded 15 delegates to the April convention in Bangor while Dole
got 3.
   In Caribou, Robertson defeated the combined forces of Bush and
Dole, 75-72, and collected all eight delegates, according to
unofficial reports.
   Gov. John R. McKernan Jr., who attended the Portland caucus to
bolster the Bush drive and conducted some of the private brokering
with the Dole campaign himself, said ``the wild card'' there and
around the state was ``how many new people who we've never seen
before the Robertson campaign is able to get out.''
   Later, he told caucus participants that they should be prepared
to unite behind the party's nominee after this summer's national
convention.
   In an overture to Robertson partisans, McKernan offered
greetings on behalf of GOP regulars, saying ``how pleased we are to
have you a part of the process.''
   Earlier, as Bush organizers sounded out the Dole camp in hopes
of blocking the proportional representation motion, Robertson
backers erupted with derisive chants of ``backroom deal'' and
``railroad.''
   State party chairwoman Karen Stram, watching the Portland
voting, acknowledged that feelings were running high in the various
camps. Stram said her job was ``to be sure that everyone comes out
of it feeling they got a fair shake.''
   She said statewide turnout in the caucuses could reach 15,000 or
more by the end of the weekend.
   ``No question, we're up three times at least'' over previous
years, she said.
   Maine's Democrats caucus on Sunday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
