<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TridentLaunch     02-27 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trident Launch,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Successfully Launches Trident 1 Missile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy Trident 1 missile was
launched successfully from a submerged submarine off Cape Canaveral
today, ending a streak of three Trident failures, officials said.
   ``It was excellent, there were no flaws whatsoever,'' said Air
Force spokesman Herb Illingworth. None of the Russian trawlers
frequently present for such launches were present, he added.
   The missile was fired down the Air Force Eastern Space and
Missile Test Range at 10:27 a.m. EST from the USS Stonewall Jackson
and landed in the Atlantic Ocean. The distance of the shot was not
released.
   It was the 55th Trident 1 launch since 1977 and the 30th from a
submerged submarine, Illingworth said.
   In the last six months, the Navy has had three consecutive
missile failures.
   A Trident 1 launched from a submarine in August 1987 failed. A
more powerful Trident 2 malfunctioned and was destroyed by remote
control after a Jan. 21 land launch. A second Trident 1 missile
blew up 18 seconds after lifting off from a submerged submarine on
Feb. 6, officials said.
</TEXT>
