<HEAD>Hart Says He Will Remain In Democratic Presidential Race</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with quotes from Hart news
conference; picks up 4th graf pvs, bgng: Questions had...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gary Hart today dispelled rumors that he would
end his presidential campaign, saying he was remaining in the
Democratic race, although acknowledging he has little chance of
winning.
   ``I came back into this race and intend to stay in this race
because the Democratic Party must have a voice for reform and
change,'' Hart said at a news conference this morning.
   Hart, who dropped out of the race and re-entered it last year
saying he wanted to ``let the people decide,'' told reporters today
that ``I've heard from the voters. I want to hear from a few more,
but I understand the message.''
   Hart said his chances of winning the Democratic presidential
nomination were ``remote, to say the least.''
   Under these political circumstances, Hart said he normally would
have decided to quit the race, but he added that ``I don't think
these are normal times.''
   Hart issued a schedule of campaign stops and speeches around the
South between now and March 4.
   Questions had arisen over whether Hart was planning to announce
he was withdrawing from the race but aides to the former Colorado
senator said earlier that he was going to stay.
   ``He is having a news conference. He's not dropping out of the
race,'' Bobbie McCallum, Hart's liaison at his Denver campaign
headquarters, said Friday.
   The five other Democratic contenders were in Atlanta for a
Georgia state Democratic Party dinner on Friday. Hart did not
attend the dinner but arrived in Atlanta late Friday and was
scheduled to participate in a Democratic debate there later today.
   Hart's campaign has failed to catch fire since he re-entered the
race in December after dropping out the previous May amid questions
about his relationship with model Donna Rice. He had been the
undisputed front-runner before he quit the race.
   In rejoining the race, Hart said he came back because ``I have
the power of ideas and I can govern this country.''
   After finishing dead last among Democrats in the New Hampshire
primary earlier this month, Hart vowed to remain in the race
despite his poor showing.
   Hart made an unsuccessful bid for the Democratic presidential
nomination in 1984.
</TEXT>
