<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     02-27 0962</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0998</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pulitzer Prize-winning author Charles Fuller
Jr. had a few words of advice for the city's black youths, so he
rented 20 billboards for a month.
   ``Young people; Stay free take pride in Yourselves, GRADUATE!!''
read the billboards featuring a young black man and woman in
graduation gowns.
   Fuller, 47, author of ``A Soldier's Play,'' spent about $7,000
on the billboards while his younger brother Walter, 23, and his son
Charles 3rd, also 23, worked out the details for the project.
   ``It is not a whole lot, really,'' Fuller said. ``But we thought
maybe something on a billboard would be a way to get the attention
of young people.''
   ``You can't go out and preach on a corner. People won't listen
to you,'' Fuller said. ``More people will read that billboard than
would ever listen to me and Walt if we stood out on Girard Avenue
handing out leaflets.''
   ``A Soldier's Play,'' about bigotry on a Southern military
outpost during World War II, when the Army was still segregated,
was made into the movie ``A Soldier's Story.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Princess Anne went
door-to-door Saturday along with health workers immunizing children
in a shanty town.
   Princess Anne, daughter of Queen Elizabeth II, walked through
Maputo's Mavalane suburb and watched young children get measles
vaccinations.
   After the visit, neighborhood women presented Princess Anne with
gifts of basketwork, pottery and printed cloth. Hundreds of young
children sang ``Long Live England.''
   Later the princess, who is president of the Save the Children
Fund, visited a pre-school class, a woman's prison and a group of
parents who have adopted orphan children.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teen-age AIDS victim Ryan White is going to
Washington, D.C., this week in hopes that his experience with the
disease will help schools cope with others like him, his mother
says.
   ``He wants to try to make it better for everybody else,'' Jeanne
White said Friday.
   Ryan and Jill Stewart, student council president at Hamilton
Heights High School, are scheduled to speak to the presidential
commission on AIDS at a public hearing Thursday.
   After Ryan, 16, was diagnosed as having acquired immune
deficiency syndrome in December 1984, Kokomo school officials and
parents fought to keep him out of school. The Whites moved to
Cicero, where Ryan was accepted by the community and enrolled in
classes.
   Ryan plans to read to the commission excerpts from a paper he
wrote for his school English class. The paper, titled The Odyssey,
recounts the problems he encountered at Kokomo, White said.
   ``He wants to tell why education is important to him and why he
wanted to go back to school. It outlines the fight to go back to
school and some of the fear and panic that happened while he was
attending school there.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television actor Alan Thicke says he
doesn't feel hypocritical about being co-host of the Miss USA
pageant, even though he belongs to eight animal-rights
organizations.
   Thicke has been criticized by animal-rights groups for his
association with the beauty contest, which will award the winner of
Tuesday's finals a full-length mink coat and a mink jacket.
   Thicke said Friday he believes he would be more valuable behind
the scenes than on the picket line with protesters who want to
educate people about the cruelties they say the fur industry
inflicts on animals.
   Last month, TV game-show host Bob Barker ended his 21-year reign
as the Miss USA master of ceremonies when he quit to protest the
mink giveaway.
   Thicke, star of ABC's ``Growing Pains'' and host of the Saturday
morning show ``Animal Crack-Ups,'' said picketing the pageant was
not the way to end animal cruelty.
   ``I invite those people to join any one of the eight groups that
I am involved with and do some of the things that we do, such as
meet with lobbyists and legislators,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spanish tenor Jose Carreras returned to
his hometown Saturday after four months in the United States to
continue his convalesence from a bone marrow transplant to treat
leukemia.
   Carreras, 42, who appeared in good health alongside his personal
physician Dr. Albert Granena, told reporters he felt ``very content
to come home.''
   Carreras spent the last four months in Seattle, where he
underwent special therapy, including a bone marrow transplant, at
the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center, a leading leukemia
treatment center.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OGDEN, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Interior Secretary James Watt says he
thinks Cuba's purported use of isolation camps for AIDS victims is
a good idea, but he says the United States lacks the courage to do
the same.
   Watt, who served under President Reagan from 1980-83, said he
favors a quarantine and called AIDS ``the first politically
protected disease in America.''
   When a member of the audience asked whether such tactics would
violate human rights, Watt responded, `Do you want an AIDS victim
to sneeze on your salad when he's serving you at a local
restaurant?''
   Experts say that acquired immune deficiency syndrome cannot be
spread through casual contact. The disease, caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, is spread most often through
sexual contact and needles or syringes shared by drug abusers.
   Speaking Thursday at Weber State College, Watt said it was his
statement about the ethnic makeup of his staff that forced him to
quit. He described his staff as including ``a black, a white, two
Jews and a cripple.''
   Watt said he now agrees it was an ``insensitive statement,'' but
feels the only offensive part of the comment was the use of the
word cripple.
   ``The new word is handicapable,'' Watt said. ``I'm from Wyoming
and didn't know that.''
</TEXT>
