<DOCNO> AP880227-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 1412EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Rdp     02-27 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Rdp,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Navy Gulf Command Changes, Force Cutback Completed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iran-Iraq, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rear Adm. Anthony A. Less took command
Saturday of the U.S. Navy's escort squadron in the Persian Gulf,
inheriting a force that U.S. officials say has lost no clout
despite a cutback in strength.
   Hours before the ceremony, two U.S. warships sailed through the
Strait of Hormuz into the gulf to complete the restructuring that
leaves 25 American warships in the region, including 16 in the
gulf-based Middle East Force.
   Less, a career aviator who once commanded the Navy's famed
``Blue Angels'' jet acrobatics team, became the 36th commander of
the Middle East Force in a shipboard ceremony that dates back to
the British navy at the time of the American Revolution in 1776.
   Government officials and gulf area diplomats attended the
wind-chilled, sunset event aboard the 17,000-ton amphibious assault
ship Coronado, newly designated flagship of the Middle East Force.
   The force has operated in the gulf since 1949, assigned to
represent and protect U.S. national interests in the vital oil
waterway.
   It attracted little recent attention until last year's
controversial decision by the Reagan administration to register 11
Kuwaiti tankers under the U.S. flag, qualifying them for American
protection from Iranian attack.
   Following that move, and the May 17 attack by an Iraqi jet on
the U.S. frigate Stark in which 37 Americans were killed, the
Navy's forces in the region grew to a peak strength of nearly 40
ships, including two battle groups in the Arabian Sea and Indian
Ocean.
   Inside the gulf, the force nearly tripled from about half a
dozen vessels to 17 at the start of 1988.
   In a speech on board the Coronado, Gen. George B. Crist, a
Marine who heads the U.S. Central Command, noted that a year ago
the United States had only about six ships in the gulf.
   ``This rapid buildup of deterrent power and the successes we
have achieved did not come easily,'' Crist said. ``Dramatic and
often traumatic decisions and efforts were required.''
   Crist's Tampa, Fla.-based headquarters is responsible for U.S.
military concerns in 19 countries from Africa to Pakistan,
encompassing the Middle East region.
   Crist also said he understood the new commander's motto was ``do
more with Less,'' an allusion to the Pentagon's move to trim the
cost and size of the escort operation by cutting the force from 17
to 16 ships.
   On Feb. 3, the 50-year-old Less also assumed command of the
Joint Task Force Middle East, the Arabian Sea support group that
also has been scaled down.
   In Saturday's ceremony, Less replaced Rear Adm. Harold J.
Bernsen, who has headed the Middle East Force since July 1986 and
before that was skipper of the flagship La Salle during the 1979
hostage crisis in Iran and the outbreak of the Iraq-Iran war in
1980.
   U.S. officials recently estimated the cost of the operations at
$15 million to $20 million a month, but said the cutback did not
result from a budget squeeze or a lessening of the Iranian threat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880227-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 1424EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SovietMissiles-US     02-27 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Missiles-US,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Official Says Soviet Missile Removal Means Little</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS_</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will make no
reciprocal gesture to Moscow's decision to withdraw some nuclear
missiles and troops from Eastern Europe, the U.S. ambassador to
NATO said Saturday.
   Alton G. Keel Jr. said the Soviet move, rather than being a
meaningful expression of good will, was part of an orchestrated
campaign to convince West Europeans that the Soviet Union is
changing its ways.
   ``We, obviously from the U.S. standpoint, welcome the fact that
they're withdrawing the missiles, but there'll be no similar action
on the part of the U.S.,'' Keel said in an interview at his
official residence outside Brussels.
   Soviet soldiers on Thursday left two bases in East Germany and
one garrison in Czechoslovakia, taking with them the first nuclear
missiles dismantled under a U.S.-Soviet treaty eliminating all
land-based nuclear rockets with ranges between 310 miles and 3,100
miles.
   The missiles moved out of East Germany and Czechoslovakia, known
in the West as SS-12s, have ranges of up to 550 miles.
   The treaty signed by President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev last Dec. 8 does not require either side to withdraw
or destroy any missiles until it has been ratified by both
governments. The U.S. Senate is expected to approve it by late
spring.
   Keel said Washington could not withdraw any of its more than 400
Tomahawk cruise and Pershing 2 ballistic nuclear missiles from
Western Europe until after the Senate decides whether to ratify the
treaty.
   He noted that the Soviets have said they will not actually
destroy any of the withdrawn SS-12 missiles until after the treaty
has been ratified by the Senate and by the Soviet parliament, the
Supreme Soviet.
   ``They obviously want to take as much advantage of their having
been willing to enter into this agreement as possible, use it to
advantage, try to convince European publics that there's been major
new thinking in the Soviet Union,'' he said.
   Keel said the United States already had shown its good will by
voluntarily halting deployment of cruise and Pershing 2 missiles as
soon as the treaty was signed.
   ``We actually did concede something unilaterally, we conceded
that we would no longer deploy systems,'' even though NATO had not
yet reached its original target of deploying 572 of the
medium-range missiles, he said.
   The Soviet move, he said, did little to increase the security of
NATO nations, which continues to be threatened by the existence of
more than 1,400 short-range Soviet nuclear missiles in Europe and a
Warsaw Pact numerical edge over the Western alliance in non-nuclear
arms.
   Keel said it ``would be meaningful'' if Moscow unilaterally
withdrew some of its shortest-range nuclear arms and conventionally
armed troops, but that NATO would make no reciprocal gesture
because its forces already are at a bare minimum to deter a
possible Soviet attack.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880227-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 1426EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w DemocraticResponse-Text     02-27 0820</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Democratic Response-Text,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Campaign Money Bjt, a0581, and AM-Reagan-Radio Text, a0572</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the Democratic Party's
response, delivered by Sen. David L. Boren of Oklahoma, to
President Reagan's radio address on Saturday:
   I welcome this chance to talk with you today, not as a
Democratic senator from Oklahoma, but as a fellow American, about a
problem that should concern all of us.
   Have you ever had the urge to start shouting, ``wake up, wake
up,'' to those around you to warn them about some danger that they
just don't seem to see?
   I had that feeling this past week as we debated about campaign
reform in the U.S. Senate.
   This issue simply does not grab the headlines like a foreign
policy emergency or a financial crisis, yet is just as serious. The
way we're financing campaigns in this country is like a silent
deadly cancer eating away at the very heart of our democratic
system.
   Too much money pumped into campaigns by too many special
interests threatens the integrity of the election process itself.
Did you know that in just 10 short years the average cost of
running a successful race for the U.S. Senate has gone up 500
percent, and that the average cost, in even small states, rose to
$3 million?
   That means that in order to finance a successful campaign for
re-election, a sitting senator must raise an average of $10,000 in
campaign contributions every single week of his or her six-year
term. That's $10,000 every week for 300 weeks in a row.
   This money chase for campaign contributions raises several
problems. First, it means that congressmen and senators are having
to spend their time and energy raising campaign money instead of
working to solve the serious problems facing our country.
   We need our Congress on the job, and not having to go out and
raise campaign funds. Second, campaigns now cost so much that
members can't raise enough to finance them from their home states
alone. They have to fly all around the country to cities in other
states where they can raise campaign funds instead of spending time
in their own states listening to the people back home to learn
about their problems.
   Finally, to raise the millions of dollars in needed campaign
funds, congressmen and senators have turned more and more to
special interest groups and political action committees known as
PACs. In the last election, almost 200 members elected to Congress
received over half of their campaign funds from PACs, often
controlled by lobbyists in Washington, instead of from the people
back home.
   What's going to happen to grassroots democracy if this trend
continues? Americans must ask themselves, is it good for our
country that the cost of campaigns has skyrocketed to $3 million?
Is it good for our country that the fastest growing source of these
funds is from narrow special interest groups based outside a
member's home state?
   The American people say no. In a recent Harris survey, 91
percent of those surveyed said this explosion of campaign costs is
a serious problem and it must be addressed. Ninety-one percent of
the American people, Democrats and Republicans alike, want their
respresentatives to act. This last week the Senate tried to act.
Fifty-two senators, over half of the members, joined in sponsoring
a bill to put limits on runaway campaign spending.
   Tragically a determined minority blocked the Senate from even
being able to consider this bill. Among Democrats the vote was 48
to 2 in favor of action. Among Republicans, it was 38 to 3 against
proceeding. I call this a tragedy because we should not break down
along party lines. We need to unite as Americans to solve this
serious problem which affects all of us.
   The supporters of the bill offered to change it to make sure it
would be fair to both political parties. But opponents said that
they would never even discuss putting limits on campaign spending.
We must not and we will not give up this fight.
   In a few weeks congressmen will spread out across this country
to speak at high school graduating ceremonies. When we urge those
students to some day think of running for office to serve their
country, will we also to have to tell them that at the current rate
of increasing campaign costs, 12 years from now when they're old
enough to run, the average U.S. Senate race will cost $15 million?
Will we have to challenge them not only to think about what they'd
like todo to help their country, but also to think about how they
will raise $15 million to run for the U.S. Senate?
   We must not let that happen to America. We must not cloud the
future of the next generation. It's time for us, all of us, to wake
up and speak out before it's too late.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880227-0100 </DOCNO>
