<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cyprus-Israel     02-27 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cyprus-Israel,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstrators Stone Israeli Embassy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Violence, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrators stoned the Israeli Embassy
and broke several windows Saturday during a protest against the
crackdown on Palestinians in Israeli-occupied territories.
   About 200 Greek Cyriots broke through a police cordon and barbed
wire barricades blocking access to the embassy building in a narrow
suburban street.
   They stood outside the tall wire fence of the embassy compound
and burned an Israeli flag, threw stones at the building and
chanted anti-Israeli slogans.
   Police reinforcements managed to drive the protesters away
within a few minutes.
   ``We have had many windows broken, but nobody has been hurt,''
said an Israeli diplomat at the embassy who answered a telephone
call from The Associated Press. He declined to give his name.
   The demonstrators marched to the embassy after staging a protest
rally in the capital's main square.
   One of the placards carried by the demonstrators said ``Dachau
lives again,'' a reference to one of the Nazi death camps where
millions of Jews were incinerated during World War II.
   Other placards said ``Palestinians have a right to
self-determination,'' and ``Israel, stop killing Palestinians.''
   The demonstration coincided with the opening session in Nicosia
of a hearing by the International Secretariat of the Inquiry
Commission Into Israeli Crimes Against the Lebanese and Palestinian
People.
   The inquiry, which held its session at a Nicosia hotel, includes
European judicial and legal personalities sympathetic to the
Palestinian cause. It is headed by British lawyer John Platts-Mills.
   Nasreen Bsisso, a Palestinian woman expelled from Israel two
years ago, told the inquiry that 138 Palestinians have been killed
and more than 2,000 have been seriously wounded since the unrest in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip started on Dec. 8.
   U.N. figures place the number of dead at 69.
   Jabril Mahmoud Rujub, 35, one of four Palestinians expelled from
Israel last month, said he had spent 17 years in Israeli prisons
and gave extensive testimony to the inquiry about prison conditions.
   ``Since there is no death penalty in Israel, they try to kill
the prisoners through torture and illtreatment,'' he said.
   Yasser Arafat, chairman of the Palestine Liberation
Organization, said in a message to the inquiry that its work ``will
unmask and expose Israeli crimes and barbaric practices.''
   He said Israel ``would not be able to carry out these barbaric
crimes without the total support and unlimited aid it receives from
the American administration.''
</TEXT>
