<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Bombs     02-27 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Bombs,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Executes Five For Planting Bombs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five people accused of planting bombs in
Iran were sentenced to death and executed Saturday, Tehran
television reported.
   The television did not identify the five nor say whether they
were among 30 people arrested earlier for allegedly planting bombs
in Tehran and western Iran in recent weeks.
   The television broadcast, monitored in Nicosia, said: ``The
Islamic Revolutionary Court announced that five agents related to
the global arrogance who were accused of planting bombs that caused
some death and injuries, were sentenced to death and executed
Saturday evening.''
   It gave no other details. But Iranian leaders and the news media
usually refer to the superpowers as global arrogance.
   The arrest of the 30 people was disclosed earlier Saturday by an
Iranian security chief in a statement broadcast on Tehran Radio.
   Sarajeddin Mussavi, commander of the Islamic Revolutionary
Committees, had said the alleged bombers were ``paid Iraqi agents''
who will shortly be handed over to revolutionary courts for trial.
   Most saboteurs are branded Iraqi agents by Iranian authorities.
Death is the usual penalty for those convicted of bombings and
several have been executed by firing squad in recent months.
   Mussavi said in an interview on the state-run radio that the
alleged saboteurs had confessed to two bombings in Tehran earlier
this month.
   The last reported bombing in the Iranian capital was Feb. 18,
when a car bomb exploded on the Mohammed Ali Jenah expressway,
wounding two people. Another 10 people were reported wounded three
days earlier in a bomb blast in north Tehran's Martyr Bahonar
Street.
   Iran and Iraq have been at war since September 1980.
</TEXT>
