<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Honduras 1stLd-Writethru a0561 02-27 0949</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0561,0966</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dope and Death Squads Rattle Honduras</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Abrams told ...,' with 1 graf to CORRECT
spelling of institution. SUBS 9th graf, `Matta, 43 ...,' with 1
graf to CLARIFY that constitution is Honduras'. SUBS 11th graf pvs,
`Political violence ...,' with 1 graf to drop word `phenomena,' and
replace it with `two.'
^An AP Extra</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drugs and political murders have
perturbed the calm that had made this Central American country an
island of peace surrounded by guerrilla wars.
   Life in this bustling capital of narrow streets and low pastel
painted buildings remains tranquil compared to the daily
tribulations of neighboring El Salvador, Nicaragua and Guatemala.
Civil wars in those countries have killed more than 100,000 people
in the past decade.
   Because of Honduras' relative stability and its close alliance
with Washington, U.S. officials were particularly concerned about
the increased use in recent years of this country as a
transshipment point for American-bound Colombian cocaine.
   After several seizures of Honduran-routed drugs in the previous
two years, federal agents in Florida last November confiscated four
tons of cocaine hidden in a shipment of Honduran wooden doors.
Worth more than $1 billion, it was the biggest bust in U.S. history.
   Elliott Abrams, assistant secretary of state for inter-American
affairs, said in an interview broadcast here last week that
``without doubt'' some Honduran military officers and government
officials are involved in the drug trade.
   Honduras returned to civilian rule in 1982 after a decade of
military regimes. But the civilian administration of President Jose
Azcona Hoyo remains weak and dependent on the support of the armed
forces.
   Abrams told the radio station HRN: ``As in any army, there are
individuals, people in the Honduran army who are not honest and
perhaps have been bought by Matta and the drug traffickers. But
that does not mean that the army as an institution is dishonest,
because that's not true.''
   He referred to Juan Ramon Matta, a Honduran who escaped from a
Colombian jail two years ago and returned here, where he lives in
an opulent home with a bodyguard of 10 former Honduran
paratroopers. Matta, allegedly a major figure of Colombia's
infamous Medellin Cartel, was jailed for a few months upon his
arrival back home. Local media said he bought his way out.
   Matta, 43, is wanted in the United States in connection with the
slaying in 1985 in Mexico of U.S drug agent Enrique Camarena
Salazar. The Honduran Constitution prohibits extradition of native
Hondurans.
   Abrams said the Honduran military asked a year ago for more U.S.
help in combating the proliferating traffickers. The U.S. Drug
Enforcement Administration, after an absence of seven years, has
re-established an office here.
   Political violence has increased along with the rise in drug
trafficking, though there is no apparent connection between the
two. Amnesty International, the London-based rights organization,
reported Wednesday that death squads linked to the Honduran
military are waging a new campaign of torture and terror against
government opponents.
   The independent Human Rights Committee, known as CODEH, blames
three slayings last month on officially sanctioned or tolerated
death squads.
   CODEH Vice President Anibal Puerto, in an interview with The
Associated Press, said there were 277 ``extra-judicial executions''
last year. He said that because of lack of investigative means, the
committee could not say how many it blames on death squads. But he
said most of the victims presented signs of torture, and that many
had been active in labor, rights, student or campesino (peasant)
organizations.
   Miguel Angel Pavon, head of the CODEH branch in the northwestern
city of San Pedro Sula, and professor Moises Landaverde were
talking in a car in front of the latter's home on Jan. 14 when a
motorcycle carrying two people pulled alongside. The motorcycle
passenger shot each man twice and the bike sped away.
   A few days earlier, gunmen killed former army sergeant Jose
Isias Vilorio, reportedly an ex-member of a death squad. Vilorio
had been scheduled to testify in Costa Rica before the
Inter-American Court on Human Rights hearing a case alleging that
death squads operated with official backing here in the early
1980s. A banner of a tiny leftist guerrilla faction was left by the
body, and the government says leftists killed him.
   Rights activists, citing the importance of Vilorio's imminent
testimony, contend he was killed by a death squad and that the flag
was a crude attempt to divert blame.
   Amnesty said other abuses, including arbitrary arrests and
torture of prisoners are widespread in Honduras.
   Consulted by the AP, Foreign Ministry spokesman Eugenio Castro
termed the Amnesty report ``somewhat pulled out of thin air ...
when there is no proof.'' He said the murders of last month were
being investigated.
   But Puerto said the investigation is getting nowhere.
   Carlos Montoya, president of the National Congress, called
during a press conference Wednesday for the abolition of death
squads.
   ``We trust that the armed forces will make known the names of
those responsible for so many crimes,'' he said.
   Authorities here reacted with indignation to the reports of
officers' involvement in the drug trade. Armed forces spokesman
Col. Manual Suarez Benavides told the AP flatly, ``There are no
military officers involved in narcotics traffic.''
   The Foreign Ministry demanded that the U.S. Embassy provide the
names of Honduran officers allegedly involved in drug dealing.
   On Feb. 19, ambassador Everett Briggs wrote to Foreign Minister
Carlos Lopez Contreras saying the U.S. government has no list of
Honduran officers involved in drug trafficking. Briggs said that if
and when U.S. authorities obtain such information, it will be
passed on to Honduran oficials.
</TEXT>
