<DOCNO> AP880227-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 1517EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VineyardView Bjt   02-27 0781</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vineyard View, Bjt,0803</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Resort Residents Want Rampant Growth Curbed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VINEYARD HAVEN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When explorer Bartholomew Gosnold
visited this small island off the Massachusetts coast in 1602, he
named it in honor of his daughter and the grapevines he found
growing abundantly on its open land.
   Today undeveloped land on Martha's Vineyard is increasingly
scarce, and an overwhelming majority of the resort island's
residents are demanding a halt to rapid growth they say is
stripping the island of its character and straining its police,
hospital and other services.
   ``At one time, it was natural graces that brought people to the
island. Now that is being supplemented by the fact that this is
also attractive as a straight out-and-out investment,'' said Walter
Renear, chairman of the Tisbury town planning board.
   A poll commissioned by the weekly Vineyard Gazette newspaper
found that 95 percent of adult residents in the island's six towns
believe development is creating serious problems. Seventy-five
percent of permanent residents and 82 percent of seasonal residents
called the problems very serious.
   The poll of 800 people by Louis Harris and Associates Inc. also
found a widespread distrust of developers and a belief among 82
percent of the respondents that the island will become unlivable if
growth is not curtailed.
   The year-round population on the island is now 12,690, more than
double what it was 15 years ago. The summer population swells to
over 90,000 with visitors in search of the island's breezes,
beaches, fishing and sailing.
   Most respondents favored a broad, one-year moratorium on
residential and commercial development and the adoption of
island-wide planning goals to restrict the number and location of
new developments.
   But Renear said speculation has helped force land values up and
a moratorium would likely draw lawsuits from developers and
property owners.
   ``It's the investment aspect of the land that is fueling this
development,'' Renear said.
   Many owners buy land and get permission to build. The permits
become part of the land value, and an investor need not build to
make money.
   For years there have been arguments about island development,
but Vineyard officials say the poll is the first indication that
there is near unanimity among residents about taking action to halt
growth.
   ``I think it's a mandate,'' said James L. Young, a member of the
Martha's Vineyard Commission, the island's regional planning
agency. ``I think it's time to take a good hard look at our
officeholders to see if they are indeed reflecting the views of
their constituents.''
   The number of building permits for new residential units on
Martha's Vineyard jumped 302 percent from 1976, when 158 permits
were issued, to 1986, when 636 new units were approved island-wide.
Another 517 units were approved in 1987, according to Vineyard
Commission records.
   Open land has become a commodity on the 100-square-mile island,
a summer haven seven miles off the Cape Cod shore. Land records
show that scores of undeveloped lots have changed hands several
times in recent years, each time at a higher price, without being
developed.
   Ironically, an agency created in May 1986 to help preserve some
of the island's scenic and historic land is benefiting from the
land deals.
   The Martha's Vineyard Land Bank receives proceeds of a 2 percent
tax on all Vineyard real estate transactions, and has collected
nearly $7.4 million, its share of the $370 million in real estate
deals on the island in the past 21 months.
   The land bank has used the money to buy outright or purchase
development rights to 290 acres and is in the process of obtaining
183 more acres.
   Efforts of the land bank and a handful of other island
preservation groups won't be enough to stop rapid development, said
Brendan O'Neill, executive director of the Martha's Vineyard
Conservation Society.
   A one-year building moratorium, he said, ``will buy us time to
forge an island-wide consensus about what we want to be as a
community.''
   But Renear, 62, a lifelong Vineyard resident, said a moratorium
is more likely to land island officials in court.
   ``This is a solvable problem and with time we can get a
solution,'' Renear said. ``There's room for growth. I'm not saying
that we have all the answers. But a moratorium is too simplistic.
Property owners will have you in court in two minutes.''
   John Magnuson, 32, who works for his father, a longtime builder
on the island, said better planning is the answer to the island's
growth problem.
   ``I don't think a moratorium is the answer,'' he said. ``I do
think it has to slow down somewhat, but there are some areas in the
back woods where growth is just fine.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
