<DOCNO> AP880227-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 1519EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VetsSkiing     02-27 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vets Skiing,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disabled Vets Ski Beyond Limits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MESA, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Swallow threw up his hands and whooped
when he crossed the finish line in his first ski race since he
broke his neck eight years ago.
   A paraplegic with only limited use of his arms, Swallow was back
on the snow again with more than 100 other disabled veterans.
   Sitting in a plastic ski sled made for disabled skiers and
grinning widely in the bright sunshine at Powderhorn Ski Area,
Swallow talked of ``paying for this in more ways than one'' but
said he thinks ``everybody should get in one of these things.''
   Swallow, 32, from Los Angeles, tore some skin from his left
elbow during his slalom run when his sled nearly overturned, but
all he cared about was getting out of his wheelchair and going
skiing.
   ``You get a lot of satisfaction out of this and it proves a lot
to people,'' said Swallow, a volunteer juvenile probation
counselor. ``Everybody can do something and there's no limit.''
   Encouraging disabled veterans to exchange their wheelchairs for
ski sleds and pushing them beyond their limits is the idea behind
the National Winter Sports Clinic for Veterans.
   Only in its second year, the clinic drew 105 disabled veterans
to Powderhorn for a week of skiing, snowmobiling, wheelchair
basketball and sightseeing.
   ``Can you imagine if you were confined to a wheelchair the
pleasure and thrill of being able to ski and going 40 mph?'' asked
Sandy Trombetta, the Veterans Administration's chief recreational
therapist in Grand Junction.
   Trombetta said most of the participants ``never even dreamed of
skiing before, and most have never pushed beyond their limitations
before.''
   The skiers ranged from near quadriplegics with only limited use
of their hands to amputees and blind skier Urban Miyares of San
Diego.
   Miyares skied with the help of Sue Haak of the Denver VA office,
who is a ski instructor for the handicapped at the Winter Park
area. She skiied next to Miyares, calling out to him when to turn,
slow down or speed up.
   Amputees ski on a single ski with tiny skis fitted to the
bottoms of their ski poles like outriggers.
   Paraplegics with good upper body coordination and balance use a
high-tech monoski, a plastic or metal shell perched on a single
ski. They also use outriggers, and accomplished monoskiers blast
through the same moguls and powder as expert able-bodied skiers.
   Most who have lost the use of their legs and have suffered some
injury higher toward the shoulders use the plastic sleds. They drag
metal spikes in the snow to turn and the less experienced are
tethered to a skier who follows to keep their speed under control.
   The plastic sleds officially are called ``sit-skis'' and cost
between $1,400 and $2,200 each.
   The veterans came from 20 states, either paying their own way to
Grand Junction or getting financial help from their local VFW or
American Legion groups. Trombetta said it costs the VA and several
corporate sponsors $50,000 to stage the week-long clinic.
   A second-year participant, Ray Hill of Detroit, says he can't
get enough of skiing.
   ``From the moment I took my first run last year I wanted to come
back,'' said Hill, 45, who was left in a wheelchair by a
hit-and-run driver.
   Hill said only the will and the mind stand in the way of the
disabled.
   ``You have to pick yourself up and do it again, and again, until
you master it,'' he said. ``And you can always look around here and
see somebody worse off than you are, doing the same thing.
   ``So if he's doing it, I can do it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880227-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 1550EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Turkey-US     02-27 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-US,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turkish Government Approves Defense Pact with U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Saturday approved the
renewal of a defense cooperation pact with the United States that
was signed by the two countries almost a year ago, the Foreign
Ministry announced.
   The pact gives the United States access to a dozen military
installations in Turkey, including two electronic listening posts
that monitor Soviet military activities and nuclear tests.
   Premier Turgut Ozal's Cabinet, disappointed by the position of
the U.S. Congress on military aid to Turkey, had been withholding
approval of the agreement that will be in force until 1990.
   Turkey contends it needs $1.2 billion in U.S. assistance a year
to modernize its armed forces.
   Last year, the Reagan administration asked Congress to give
Turkey $914 million in aid. The Congress, citing budget
constraints, cut the request to $570 million and reduced the amount
to $490 million for the current fiscal year.
   The announcement said that in ratifying the agreement, the
Turkish government considered other aspects of the relationship
with the United States besides defense cooperation. It did not
elaborate.
   The announcement also noted that the United States, in the
agreement, had pledged to make it easier for Turkey to repay its
foreign military sales credits and also pledged to improve trade
relations between the two countries.
   It was not made public what kind of negotiations took place
before the Turkish government's decision to approve the agreement.
   The 1980 agreement expired in 1985, and it was extended until
1990 last March following intense negotiations.
   Legally, the agreement goes into force after confirmation by the
Cabinet and publication in the official gazette.
   The announcement said the gazette will publish the government's
decision on Sunday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
