<DOCNO> AP880227-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 1554EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-US     02-27 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-US,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Protests Lack of Security During Anti-American Demonstration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States lodged a protest with
the government for failing to protect a U.S. Navy supply ship
during an anti-American demonstration on the island of Crete, an
embassy spokesman said Saturday.
   Four islanders and two American sailors from the supply ship
Saturn were injured during Wednesday's dockside demostration at
Heraklion harbor. The ship, which sailed Thursday, called at the
port to pick up fresh fruit and vegetables for the 6th Fleet in the
Mediterranean.
   ``The U.S. Embassy has issued a protest over the lack of
security afforded during the incident,'' said the embassy
spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The spokesman said the protest was delivered to the Greek
Foreign Ministry Friday by embassy Charge d'Affairs Ed Cohen.
   More than 1,000 demonstrators gathered at the port, sprayed
``Americans Go Home'' in red paint on the ship's side, cut and set
fire to a mooring cable, and hurled rocks, bottles and flares.
   Demonstrators claimed that sailors aboard the Saturn tossed the
bottles, rocks and other objects back into the crowd. The protest
was organized by a local peace group opposed to the American
military presence on Crete.
   ``The government is waiting ... for the Heraklion port
authority's report based on which a reply will be given,'' said
government spokesman Yiannis Roubatis.
   He said that if the findings cast blame ``on the behavior of the
American ship's crew during the demonstration, a protest will be
made to the American side.''
   There is an American Air Force base near Heraklion as well as
air and naval facilities for American warships at Souda Bay in
western Crete.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
