<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Crash 2ndLd-Writethru   02-27 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0609,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Airliner Carrying 51 Crashes Near Siberia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to delete extraneous word.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Aeroflot airliner carrying 51 people crashed on
a Siberian runway and burst into flames as it finished the final
leg of a cross-country trip, killing and injuring passengers, Tass
said.
   The Soviet news agency quoted a local aviation official as
saying the Tu-134 ``fell within the airfield boundaries, broke up
and caught fire'' at the city of Surgut, an oil and petrochemical
center on the Ob River about 1,400 miles east of Moscow.
   ``Unfortunately, there were victims,'' Tass said. An earlier
report said: ``There is loss of life.''
   Tass said the Tu-134 was carrying 45 passengers and six crew
members, but did not specify how many people were killed and
injured in the crash, which occurred shortly after 4 a.m. Moscow
time.
   It was the third reported fatal crash of a commercial jetliner
in the Soviet Union this year.
   Fire engines and rescue vehicles were at the crash site within
two minutes and were giving first aid to the injured, Tass quoted
the local deputy chief of civil aviation, Yuri Evreinov, as saying.
   Tass said 15 emergency vehicles were sent to the Surgut airport
to evacuate victims, who were taken to two hospitals.
   Eight doctors also were brought in from the regional center of
Tyumen, Tass said.
   Tass said the 1,600-mile flight originated in the Byelorussian
capital of Minsk, with stops in the Volga basin industrial city of
Kuibyshev and Tyumen, a Siberian oil city, before a final scheduled
landing in Surgut, a city of more than 150,000 people located in
western Siberia.
   The Tu-134 is a twin-turbofan plane designed for short- and
medium-range flights, and can carry from 80 to 96 passengers,
according to Jane's All the World's Aircraft.
   The causes of the crash are being investigated by a special
government commission, Tass said.
   ``The weather this morning was good, communications with the
plane solid,'' Evreinov was quoted as saying. ``But then the
unforeseen happened.''
   Tass said the Soviet government had conveyed its condolences to
people injured in the crash and to the families of the dead.
   In the past, the Soviet Union rarely reported its plane crashes,
but Deputy Civil Aviation Minister Ivan Vasin told The Associated
Press last fall that Aeroflot would begin publishing reports on its
accidents this year.
   The policy change was clearly linked to Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's campaign for ``glasnost,'' or openness, on some social
issues.
   On Jan. 18, a Tu-154 passenger jet crashed on landing at the
Caspian Sea port of Krasnovodsk, and Soviet media said 11 people
were killed and 12 hurt.
   Those media reports, which were issued on the day of the crash,
marked the first time the state-run Soviet press and broadcast
media reported on a domestic air accident the same day it occurred.
   On Jan. 25, an Aeroflot Yakovlev-40 tri-turbofan passenger plane
crashed near the airport in the Siberian city of Nizhnevartovsk.
Tass at the time said the crash caused ``loss of life,'' but did
not say how many people had died.
   Vladimir Y. Potemkin, deputy chief of flight services at the
Ministry of Civil Aviation, told a news conference earlier this
month that a total of 47 people were killed last year in accidents
involving Aeroflot planes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
