<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Park Yong-shik can shed his toupee now
that Chun Doo-hwan is no longer president.
   The popular television actor says he had to wear a hairpiece
during Chun's seven-year term because he bears a striking
resemblance to the balding former president, who was succeeded
Thursday by Roh Tae-woo.
   Park, 44, said he was banned from appearing on state-run
television in 1981 without explanation. Park said he learned later
it was because he resembled the Chun.
   Authorities in 1982 accepted his proposal to wear a toupee and
grow a beard to change his appearance, he said. However, he lost
important roles in soap operas and other programs and only received
minor parts in historical dramas.
   ``I hope such a comic thing will never happen again,'' Park said
Friday.
