<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Panda     02-27 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Panda,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pandas' Bamboo Shortage Crisis Improving</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's giant pandas, in danger of extinction
since 1983 when their dietary staple of bamboo began to wither, are
over the worst of the crisis, China's top forestry official was
quoted Saturday as saying.
   Forestry Minister Gao Dezhan said new bamboo has started to grow
in the pandas' three native provinces of Sichuan, Shaanxi and
Gansu, the official People's Daily reported.
   But he said the threat to the pandas is not over because the
animals don't generally like young bamboo.
   Gao called on the leaders of the three provinces to continue to
guard the pandas' safety. The officials met Friday in Beijing to
discuss the situation.
   At the meeting, Gao called for strict punishment, including the
death penalty, for hunters who capture or kill giant pandas.
   China's panda population, now just under 1,000, has been
declining for the past five years in part because a rare flowering
cycle of the arrow bamboo caused more than 275,000 tons of the
plant to wither and die.
   Eleven men were sentenced earlier this week to prison terms
ranging from three years to life for killing two giant pandas in
Sichuan province.
</TEXT>
