<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Imports     02-27 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Imports,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Official Denies Import Liberalization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing Liberal Democratic Party will not
accept a United States request that Japan lift restrictions on
imported beef and oranges within two years, a party official was
quoted as saying Saturday.
   Michio Watanabe, chairman of the party's Policy Affairs Research
Council, told a news conference that Japan instead would offer the
United States an increase in import quotas, Kyodo News Service
reported.
   ``There are people in the United States saying many things, but
we don't accept them,'' it quoted him as saying in reference to
U.S. demands that imports of oranges and beef be liberalized.
   Party officials were not immediately available Saturday to
confirm the report.
   On Thursday, a senior Economic Planning Agency official
predicted that Japanese import restrictions on beef would be lifted
within two years, with a lifting of restrictions on citrus fruit
coming even sooner.
   Japan has been under pressure from the United States and
Australia to open its beef and citrus markets, with an agreement
governing imports of the two products due to expire in March.
   But the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries has
opposed liberalization, arguing that it is unfair to single out
Japan and pointing to restrictions that the United States maintains
on beef imports.
   Japanese officials have said the quotas are neccessary to
protect Japanese farmers.
   The current agreement between Japan and the United States called
for Japan to increase its beef import quotas from 141,000 tons a
year in 1984 to 177,000 tons by 1988, and its orange quotas by
1,100 tons each year until 1988. The level was 82,000 tons in 1984,
when the agreement was signed.
</TEXT>
