<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Armenia     02-27 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstrations Said To End In Armenian Capital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN GILMOUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reports from Armenia's capital indicated the city
was calm Saturday, but a U.S.-based group claimed some Armenians
remained camped in a tent city in the region where several days of
mass protests had been held.
   A hotel manager in Yerevan, reached by telephone from Moscow,
said, ``Everything is quiet'' in the capital city where at least
five days of street protests brought an appeal by Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev for restraint.
   A telephone operator in Yerevan also said the demonstrations had
ended. Efforts to contact Armenian nationalist leaders were
unsuccessful. Both the operator and the hotel manager spoke on
condition they not be identified.
   There was no direct word on the situation in Nagorno-Karabakh,
the autonomous region where members of the ethnic Armenian majority
began the demonstrations to protest the Soviet Communist Party's
rejection of a proposal to give the region back to Armenia. It has
been designated part of the neighboring republic of Azerbaidzhan
since 1923.
   Most telephone calls to Yerevan have been cut off since the
demonstrations began, and foreign reporters have been prevented
from traveling to the small republic on the Turkish border.
   Gorbachev's appeal, read on Armenian and Azerbaidzhanian radio
and television Friday by a Central Committee official, was
accompanied by a pledge from local party officials to ask the
Moscow-based Communist Party Central Committee to reconsider the
territorial issue.
   Reports from Armenia said that after the appeal, the
demonstrators in Yerevan, said by some to have numbered up to 1
million, began to disperse.
   A Washington-based group calling itself the Armenian National
Committee of America quoted telephone reports from the region as
saying Nagorno-Karabakh's main city, Stepanakert, had been turned
into a tent city by Armenian villagers from the countryside.
   The group claimed Azerbaidzhanis had killed 70 Armenians in the
region and that Soviet troops were stationed around Stepanakert to
prevent further ethnic violence. There have been other reports of
deaths in the region, but they have not been confirmed.
   Relations between Azerbaidzhan, a predominantly Moslem republic,
and mainly Christian Armenia have been tense for some time. Last
week, there were disturbances in the contested autonomous region,
where the population is three-quarters Armenian, and they spread to
Yerevan.
   The protests brought concessions from regional Communist Party
leaders. They named a 56-year-old Armenian, Genrikh Pogosyan, to
head the party in Nagorno-Karabakh, replacing Boris Kevorkov who
also is an ethnic Armenian but apparently less popular than
Pogosyan.
</TEXT>
