<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BeachedWhales     02-27 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beached Whales,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report 30 Whales Beached on Gulf of California Coast</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mexico-Whales, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty pilot whales perished after they
beached on the Gulf of California coast. A biologist said Saturday
the cause of death was unknown but the mass beaching of pilot
whales is a natural phenomenon.
   ``They are whales that normally beach in large groups,'' said
Luis Fleischer, a program director of the federal Fishing
Department, in a telephone interview from Baja California.
   He said the 26 male and four female whales beached about five
days ago along a three-mile stretch of Northern Baja California's
gulf coastline.
   ``They all are dead now and in an advanced state of
decomposition,'' Fleischer said.
   Adult pilot whales are about 9-15 feet long.
   Fleischer said the area is about 155 miles north of the zone
where the government intends to declare a land and sea wildlife
preserve. The preserve is intended to protect the gray whale, a
once nearly extinct species, which reproduces in the lagoons on
Baja California's Pacific coast.
   ``It has nothing to do with the reserve,'' Fleischer said of the
deaths of the pilot whales. The reserve is in Southern Baja
California state.
   The biologist said research would be done to determine if
weather conditions or what other reasons might be responsible for
the beaching.
   The newspaper Excelsior quoted Augusto Ferrer MacGregor, a
representative for the Fishing Department in Northern Baja
California, as saying that for the past two months about 1,000
pilot whales have been in the area where the beaching took place.
</TEXT>
