<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RacialAttack 1stLd-Writethru a0620 02-27 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Racial Attack, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0620,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Seek White Men In Racial Attack On Black Woman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with detail from rally in New
York, picking up 5th graf pvs, `In the...'. SUBS 10th graf, `The
coalition...', to CORRECT amount of reward offered in New Jersey
case to $1,000 sted $10,000. Note language in 3rd graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEWTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black woman was attacked by two white men
who smeared her with excrement, painted markings on her face and
clipped her hair, police said Saturday.
   The injured woman was hospitalized for 12 days after the
incident earlier this month, police said. They said they were
unsure whether it was a ``copycat'' attack patterned after the
highly publicized case of a black girl in Wappingers Falls, N.Y.
   That girl, Tawana Brawley, 16, was found last November wrapped
in a plastic garbage bag and covered with excrement. The word
``nigger'' and ``KKK'' were scrawled on her body and she said she
had been sexually assaulted by six white men. Some of her hair also
had been chopped off.
   About 600 demonstrators marched peacefully through Poughkeepsie,
N.Y., Saturday to protest the treatment of Miss Brawley and the
stalled investigation of the assault.
   ``We come to you with hate in our eyes,'' said lawyer Alton
Maddox Jr., addressing Gov. Mario Cuomo rhetorically. ``We come to
you with hate in our hearts. You are not talking to
foot-shufflers.''
   The protest leaders have been calling on Cuomo to remove state
Attorney General Robert Abrams from the case. Cuomo had named
Abrams as a special prosecutor to investigate the case after two
local prosecutors claimed conflicts of interest.
   The leaders want a new, permanent prosecutor named for statewide
race-related crimes. They have said the victim and her family won't
cooperate with the investigation until then.
   The case has grown into a cause celebre among some civil rights
activists, and actor Bill Cosby posted a reward for information in
the investigation.
   In the Newton case, the victim was attacked Feb. 8 in a
stairwell outside her downtown apartment. She was not sexually
assaulted, police said.
   Police Detective John Tomasula said he believes the attack was
racially motivated because of statements the men made to the
victim. Tomasula declined to disclose what they said. The
assailants were believed to be in their 20s.
   Police believe the assault was not premeditated against the
woman, Hildegard Smith.
   ``I'm sure if anyone went down (the stairwell), something was
going to happen,'' Tomasula said. ``She was in the wrong place at
the wrong time and they just took advantage of her.''
   Ms. Smith, 50, was treated for trauma for 12 days at Newton
Memorial Hospital, said the Rev. William Sadler, one of the leaders
of a community coalition.
   The coalition, made up of mostly white clergy and civic leaders,
is offering a $1,000 reward for information leading to the arrest
of the assailants.
   Ms. Smith's family last week gave permission for the coalition
to disclose her name and condition to help catch her attackers,
Sadler said.
   ``We wanted the people to know what had happened,'' he said.
``We wanted to support the woman and wanted to bring the whole
community together to say we don't want this kind of thing to
happen.''
</TEXT>
