<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Democrats-Trade     02-27 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Trade,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Rivals Pound Gephardt For Trade Position</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Democrats Debate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Richard Gephardt's Democratic presidential
rivals wrote an obituary for his trade policies Saturday, but
Michael Dukakis said ``burial has been postponed until after Super
Tuesday in deference to the next of kin.''
   Gephardt, whose legislation would penalize foreign countries
that have trade surpluses with the United States, told his
opponents during a campaign debate that his measure seeks to
discourage other countries from being protectionist.
   The House included Gephardt's provision in the sweeping trade
bill, but no such language appears in the Senate's version of the
legislation.
   House-Senate negotiators say they are unlikely to take action on
the proposal until after the Super Tuesday primaries March 8. Most
participants say they expect Gephardt's amendment to be changed.
   ``The Gephardt amendment is dead,'' Dukakis told the Missouri
congressman during one exchange. ``You know that.''
   ``I don't know that, Mike,'' Gephardt responded. ``Where did you
hear that?''
   ``It's burial has been postponed until after Super Tuesday in
deference to the next of kin, but it's dead,'' the Massachusetts
governor said to laughter from the audience.
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr., D-Tenn., said it would be ``false and
misleading'' to imply that unfair trading practices by other
countries account for more than 10 to 15 percent of the U.S. trade
deficit.
   ``The real answer is not just bashing other countries,'' said
Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill. ``The real answer is having an effective
president who understands the issue and then moves.''
   Moments later, former Sen. Gary Hart of Colorado said, ``The
worst idea put forward in this campaign is protectionism.''
   He said Gephardt's amendment ``will lead us toward a trade war,
at least increase the likelihood of that trade war, which in turn
could trigger market crashes and depressions.''
   ``Gary, your thinking is stuck in the past,'' Gephardt said.
   ``Yours is,'' said Hart, as the two men, seated side by side,
pointed fingers at each other.
   ``Why do we continually apologize for unfair trade practices by
other countries ... ,'' Gephardt asked. ``All I'm saying is let's
stand up for the fairness for our people.''
</TEXT>
