<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 1906EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Violence 3rdLd-Writethru   02-27 0846</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Violence, 3rd Ld - Writethru,a0652,0866</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers Kill Two Arabs; Hundreds Rally Against Shultz Mission</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 6th pvs: The army ... to UPDATE with
army saying four soldiers will be tried in military court. Pickup
7th pvs: The clashes in ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers killed three Palestinians
during clashes in the occupied territories Saturday, hospital
officials said. Police detained two American teachers carrying
posters listing the names of slain Arabs.
   Arabs burned tires and threw rocks in Jerusalem and other
Israeli cities to protest the peace mission of U.S. Secretary of
State George P. Shultz, while a group of Israelis held a rally in
support of the initiative.
   On the occupied West Bank of the Jordan River, protesters
clashed with soldiers in Hebron, the nearby village of Halhoul and
an Arrub refugee camp. The army said soldiers killed two
Palestinians and wounded 15.
   Hospital officials said three people were killed, including
17-year-old Maged Al Atrash of Halhoul who died of gunshot wounds
to the abdomen late Saturday at Jerusalem's Mukassad hospital. The
doctors said 27 people were wounded.
   Soldiers fatally shot Nihad Abdul Ghafour, 20, of Arrub and
Baker Abdullah Al Bao, 17, of Halhoul, according to the hospital
officials. The deaths brought to 71 the number of Palestinians
killed by Israelis since the recent wave of unrest began Dec. 8.
   The army reported Saturday that a 15-month-old Jewish child
suffered a broken skull when assailants hurled a stone at his
family's car in Jerusalem in an attack Friday.
   Israel radio quoted the army's West Bank commander, Maj. Gen.
Amram Mitzna, as saying Saturday that four soldiers would be tried
in a military court on charges they beat two Arabs who were lying
on the ground and had their hands tied behind their backs.
   The soldiers were detained Friday and their commanding officer,
a captain, was suspended after CBS television filmed the beatings
Thursday in the West Bank city of Nablus and showed the footage to
Mitzna. The general also ordered the release of the two Arabs.
   The film was shown on television stations in several European
countries, and Foreign Ministry officials said Saturday that
Israeli embassies in Europe received dozens of telegrams protesting
the beatings.
   The clashes in Halhoul and Arrub began when masked youths
blocked the main Jerusalem-Hebron highway, the army said. Soldiers
fired tear gas, rubber bullets and gunshots to drive the
stone-throwers away from the highway.
   For several hours, soldiers surrounded Hebron's Alia Hospital,
firing tear gas at stone-throwing demonstrators nearby, said a
nurse, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The army imposed curfews on the areas around Hebron, but allowed
Jewish settlers to move freely, military officials said. The army
also extended curfews on four Gaza Strip refugee camps, restricting
120,000 people, or nearly 10 percent of the 1.5 million Arabs in
the occupied territories, to their homes.
   In the West Bank city of Ramallah, police detained American
teachers Alison Glick, 25, of Cincinnati, and John Benvenuto, in
his 40s, of Albany, N.Y., because they allegedly possessed inciting
material, said Joost Hiltermann, a friend of the two and researcher
for the Ramallah-based civil rights group Law in the Service of Man.
   Ramallah police refused to discuss the case.
   Hiltermann said Ms. Glick and Benvenuto were detained while
walking in Ramallah and carrying posters with names of Palestinians
killed by Israelis in the past 11 weeks.
   Benvenuto and Ms. Glick, teachers at a Quaker school in
Ramallah, were not allowed to see a lawyer, said Hiltermann.
   David Good, a spokesman for the U.S. Consulate in east
Jerusalem, said he was informed of the detentions but could not
elaborate.
   In Jerusalem, about 3,000 Israelis attended a rally organized by
the ``Peace Now'' movement near the home of Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir. Demonstrators carried banners reading `Say yes to the peace
initiative.''
   Speakers urged the government to trade land for peace, a formula
advocated by Shultz, but opposed by Shamir.
   Also in Jerusalem, Palestinian protesters blocked roads near the
Shufat refugee camp, throwing stones and burning tires. Police
dispersed the crowd with rubber bullets and arrested six protesters.
   About 3,000 police officers, double the usual number, were
deployed in Jerusalem after Palestinian organizers last week called
for stepped-up protests during the five-day Shultz visit.
   Shultz, on a mission to seek agreement on guidelines for
starting Arab-Israeli talks, met with Syrian and Jordanian leaders
in Damascus and Amman Saturday and returned to Jerusalem later in
the day.
   In northern Israel, meanwhile, hundreds of left-wing Israeli
Arabs took to the streets to protest the Shultz visit and the
Israeli crackdown on the protests. There were no reports of
violence, and police did not interfere.
   Four hundred protesters demonstrated in Umm el Fahm, a town of
30,000, the site of frequent anti-Israeli violence. In the Arab
town of Shefaram, also in northern Israel, about 300 Israeli Arabs
demonstrated.
   Since the protests began in the occupied territories, many of
Israel's 700,000 Arab citizens have expressed support for their
brethren in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</TEXT>
