<1ST_LINE>u i AM_Banker-Guinness     02-27 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM_Banker-Guinness,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irish Banker John Guinness Killed in Mountain Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGOR, Wales (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irish banker John Guinness, whose wife was
kidnapped two years ago and held captive for eight days, was
fatally injured Saturday in a 500-foot fall on Snowdon Mountain in
north Wales, police reported.
   They said Guinness, a cousin of members of the Guinness brewing
family, was accompanied on the climb by his 49-year-old wife,
Jennifer, their son Ian and three friends. Guinness, 52, plunged
from the snow-covered path as the party descended from the summit
of the 3,560-foot mountain, according to police.
   Guinness suffered multiple injuries and was airlifted off the
mountain by a Royal Air Force helicopter but was dead on arrival at
a hospital in Bangor, 10 miles away.
   A police spokesman said, ``They were ill-equipped for such a
walk bearing in mind the conditions.
   ``The weather was not particularly bad but the conditions
underfoot were very hazardous where the accident occurred.''
   The couple had three children.
   Jennifer Guinness was kidnapped from the family home near Dublin
April 8, 1986, and held captive for a ransom of two million Irish
pounds _ then $2.6 million.
   Eight days later, police besieged the hideout where she was held
and freed her without payment of the ransom.
   Her three abductors surrendered and three other people were
arrested later.
   Mrs. Guinness was praised by police for keeping calm and playing
a key role in the negotiations during the siege.
   Guinness was chairman of the Dublin merchant bank Guinness and
Mahon.
   On the day of his wife's abduction, he returned home from work
to find her and their 23-year-old daughter, Gillian, tied up. The
abductors pistol-whipped him and tied him. Two and a half hours
after they fled he managed to free himself and telephoned police.
   The Guinnesses were married in 1959. Their third child, Tania,
is in her 20s.
   Guinness was regarded as one of Ireland's finest long-distance
sailors and once sailed the Atlantic with his wife.
   He was sixth cousin of the titular head of the centuries-old
family, the third Earl of Iveagh. The earl is chairman of the world
famous brewery that bears the family name.
</TEXT>
