<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Labor     02-27 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Labor,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Left Wing Wins Control of Britain's Biggest Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hard-line leftists won control of Britain's
largest union Saturday at a time when the union-financed Labor
Party is seeking to moderate its stance after three successive
electoral defeats.
   The Transport and General Workers Union, with 1.4 million
members nationwide, elected 23 hard-left candidates to its
39-member National Executive Council. The moderate faction
supporting Labor Party leader Neil Kinnock previously had a 21-18
majority.
   The transport workers union has a 1,250,000 block vote for the
equivalent of 20 percent of the total voting power at the Labor
Party conference and could create obstacles for reforms Kinnock is
seeking.
   Welsh-born Kinnock, 45, who took over the leadership in 1983,
waged a polished campaign in the June 1987 general election but
still lost resoundingly to Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's
Conservatives.
   At the Labor Party conference in September, Kinnock told the
delegates the 87-year-old party must ``face the realities of
changing society. ... What do you say to a docker who earns 400
pounds ($700) a week, owns his house, a new car, microwave and
video? You do not say `Let me take you out of your misery
brother.'''
   The party then voted overwhelmingly for a policy review.
   Ron Todd, union general secretary, said Saturday, ``The policy
of our union will be maintained. Our support for the (Labor) party
and its leader will be maintained.''
   ``We are involved in the Labor Party on an exercise on policy
review,'' he added. ``Our union will take its decision on the
review policy but it has always given consistent support to the
party. It's not a blank check and Mr. Kinnock knows that.''
   Dennis Skinner, left-wing Labor member of Parliament and a
member of the party's ruling national executive, said: ``This
result, together with the Ford strike and the (National Health
Service) campaign, indicates a new-found belief in strong trade
unionism, and every socialist should welcome these results.
   ``The left has had a few lean years. Now, the omens look rather
better.'' Auto workers struck all the British plants of Ford Motor
Co. Feb. 8-11th in Britain's first major industrial strike in three
years.
   The workers had rejected their leaders' recommendation that they
accept offered pay increases and a three-year contract. Instead
they won an increased pay settlement and a two-year pact. Labor
leaders called it the first significant union victory in seven
years.
   Nurses staged a one-day strike Feb. 3 to protest their hours and
wages and express concern for the condition of the publicly
financed National Health Service. They said it must have more
resources.
</TEXT>
