<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SAfrica-Protest     02-27 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Protest,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White Extremist Group Condemns `Sellout' Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 5,000 members of a
right-wing paramilitary group rallied Saturday to demand a
whites-only state in South Africa and urge the government to
strengthen apartheid legislation.
   Members of the Afrikaner Resistance Movement held a four-hour
ceremony in Pretoria, saying the government was attempting to
``sell out'' its whites. The group also burned the flag of the
African National Congress, an outlawed black guerrilla group that
supports majority black rule.
   The protesters, many wearing uniforms and carrying pistols, said
prayers, sang and waved flags.
   They commemorated an 1881 victory by the Afrikaners over the
British in the town of Majuba, which leader Eugene TerreBlanche
said was symbolic of the Afrikaners' present-day struggle to
establish a homeland.
   ``The day is coming when this government will capitulate (to
blacks),'' TerreBlanche said. ``The AWB must prepare ... because
that is when we will take over the country.''
   ``If you scrap the apartheid laws, you can expect South Africa
to follow the same route as the other (African) colonies, which
have decayed and rotted,'' he said. ``Without apartheid laws we
cannot have order. And without order this country will
disintegrate.''
   Apartheid, by law and custom, establishes a racially segregated
society in which South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
   The demonstration followed Wednesday's government crackdown
which banned 18 of the country's leading black opposition groups
from engaging in politics.
   TerreBlance did not comment on the crackdown.
   After the meeting, group members traveled to the Union
Buildings, the government's executive headquarters, to present a
petition calling for a whites-only state in South Africa.
   Riot police blocked the entrance to the building, but accepted
the petition from TerreBlanche. There were no reports of violence
or arrests.
   The right-wing group is made up almost exclusively of
Afrikaners, the Dutch-descended settlers of South Africa. The group
rejects all concessions from South Africa's 5 million whites to the
nation's 26 million black majority.
   In other developments Saturday, security forces began erecting a
five-foot barbed-wire fence around most of the KTC squatter camp
outside Cape Town.
   The KTC camp has been the site of ongoing faction fighting among
rival black groups in recent weeks. Police said two people were
killed and 20 shacks were flattened in fighting last week.
   Witnesses said the fence, which stretched for more than a mile,
had three openings for residents to enter and exit. Several
thousand people live in the KTC camp.
   In June 1986, 70,000 people lost their homes and scores of
people were killed in KTC and three other sections of the
Crossroads squatter complex during an onslaught by black vigilantes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
