<DOCNO> AP880227-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 2123EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NoriegaInvestigation     02-27 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Noriega Investigation,0642</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Indictment Sparked By Wayward Cocaine Shipment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot who abandoned a twin-engine Cessna along
a closed highway in September 1985 left behind nearly a ton of
cocaine and the clue eventually led to the indictment of Panamanian
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, a newspaper reported Saturday.
   The Cessna's pilot, Anthony Azpruia, told prosecutors about the
Noriega link after his arrest, The Miami Herald reported. His
cooperation and implication of Miami-based aircraft parts business
DIASCA sparked an investigation.
   The investigation of alleged Panamanian drug trafficking was
completed by Miami-based federal officials whose information was
ignored by Drug Enforcement Administration officials in the U.S.
Embassy in Panama City and in Washington, according to a Senate
Foreign Relations subcommittee counsel and the chief assistant U.S.
attorney in Miami.
   ``There's absolutely no question that, through all the
administrations since 1969, we had more than adequate information
that this guy (Noriega) was a dope dealer and chose to ignore it,''
said Richard Gregorie, chief assistant U.S. attorney in Miami.
   ``Even when we wanted to indict him, there were two factions
within the DEA,'' he said. ``People were satisfied with what they
were getting out of Panama, that he was doing enough. The other
faction wanted to work the case. We really didn't send a lot up to
Washington. We stayed clear of it.''
   DIASCA had already been penetrated by DEA agent Dan Moritz when
pilot Azpruia made his emergency landing on a closed section of
Interstate 75 in south Florida on Sept. 25, 1985.
   Running out of fuel and pursued by a DEA helicopter, Azpruia
landed and abandoned the $1 million plane and its cargo, about 900
kilograms or roughly 1,980 pounds of cocaine.
   Moritz said DIASCA president Alfredo Caballero provided aircraft
for ``cocaine-smuggling ventures'' by 38-year-old pilot Floyd
Carlton, who is now the government's key witness against Noriega.
   Moritz said the DIASCA office was used for ``planning smuggling
ventures, for assembling and distributing large cash proceeds of
narcotics transactions and for placing telephone calls.''
   Caballero denies any involvement in drug trafficking.
   Four months after the Cessna's highway landing, Caballero, his
son, Azpruia, Carlton and three others were indicted. All were
jailed but Carlton, who was in Panama.
   Azpruia told prosecutors that there was a Noriega connection,
but investigators needed Carlton to make a case.
   Carlton was pursued not only by authorities in Florida but by
drug lords in Colombia who believed he had stolen a cocaine
shipment of more than 1,100 pounds from them, the Herald reported.
   Carlton was so worried that he went to the U.S. Embassy in
Panama City and told DEA agents there about Noriega's alleged role
in the drug smuggling.
   ``When I mentioned the name of General Noriega, they immediately
became upset, and I noticed that. Of course, I became nervous at
that point,'' Carlton has said.
   The embassy confession was a bungled opportunity, said Jack
Blum, counsel to a Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee.
   ``The minute the boys hear what he's got, they turn cold, like
he's a lunatic,'' Blum said. ``When he tells them about Noriega,
there's an understanding that this isn't a healthy place to talk
about it.''
   ``He was seeking help. But he wasn't seeking help as far as
being willing to come to the United States and testify,'' Gregorie
said.
   Carlton eventually went to Colombia, confronted the drug lords
and, with a kind word from the boss of Colombia's Medellin Cartel,
the pressure was reduced, the newspaper said.
   Miami investigators used Caballero to set up a trap in Costa
Rica to capture Carlton. Since then, Carlton has given detailed
depositions about drug flights he says he flew to the United States
under arrangement with Noriega and has testified before the Senate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
