<DOCNO> AP880227-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 2138EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GacyLetters 2ndLd-Writethru a0668 02-27 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gacy Letters, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0668,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Prints Portions Of Letters Sent From Gacy To Woman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead and 7th graf, `The portions...', to CORRECT that
all letters quoted were published in Sunday editions of the
newspaper, which becomes available Saturday, sted published
Saturday and Sunday. Picks up 8th graf, `K_He said...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Serial killer John Wayne Gacy believes he will be
paroled, cried while watching the Olympics and says ``It doesn't
always pay to be good to people,'' according to letters published
Sunday.
   The letters were written by Gacy and sent to Sue Terry, 43, of
Centralia. She says Gacy has proposed and she would marry him, the
Chicago Sun-Times said in Sunday's early editions.
   Gacy, 45, now on death row, was convicted of killing 33 young
men and boys, 29 of whom were found buried under or near his home
outside Chicago.
   ``I don't believe hardly any of it,'' Ms. Terry told the
Sun-Times. ``I really don't. ... He doesn't think he's guilty. To
me he don't seem like he could hurt anyone.
   ``We're real close,'' she said. ``I like John, and he trusts me.
I guess I love him. Yes.''
   Gacy wrote 41 letters to Ms. Terry, who is divorced, from Oct.
5, 1986, to Feb. 16, 1988. She shared some of them with the
newspaper and the Sun-Times said it would publish the letters for a
week.
   The portions published in Sunday's editions, which became
available Saturday, ranged from Gacy's thoughts on freedom to his
disdain for Queen Elizabeth II:
   _He said he was moved by the performance of Olympic speed skater
Dan Jansen, whose sister died while he was competing in Calgary.
   ``She wanted him to go on and skate for her. And in the first
turn he lost his balance and fell. The tears just rolled down my
face. And I don't even know him,'' Gacy wrote.
   _Ms. Terry asked Gacy about an eventual release from prison.
   ``You asked me what I'll do when I get my freedom. I don't deal
in fantasy that much. It will be hard. Don't forget it may be as
long as 10 years before I get this monkey off my back. And that's a
lot to make up for as I have eight years or more done already.''
   ``I have land in five states. Most of it is where I don't want
to live _ Florida, Arizona, Illinois, Wisconsin and Minnesota. Hey,
you want to live on an island? I think that would be great.
   ``If you got mad at someone, they couldn't get away from you.''
   In another letter quoted in Sunday's editions, Gacy had more to
say about what he would do if free.
   ``I am being sued for $697 million right now. Start paying that
off,'' he wrote. ``The numbers don't mean a thing, as they can have
it all. Just give me my freedom. I'll make what I need so fast
anyway as I have a knack for making money.
   ``I already told you what kind of house I am going to build. ...
I am going to make it a halfway house for horny girls and party my
butt off in orgies. Can you dig it?'' Many of the boys and young
men Gacy is convicted of killing had been sexually molested before
they died, prosecutors said.
   _Gacy says he has no affection for Britain's Queen Elizabeth.
   ``I can't stand royalty. When people are starving, we have these
sissy types wasting money. ... Since when do you bow to another
human being? They are no better than you.''
   In another letter, Gacy writes, ``It doesn't always pay to be
good to people, even family.''
   Ms. Terry could not be reached for comment by telephone
Saturday; there is no telephone listing for her in Centralia.
   Marvin Ziporyn, a Chicago forensic psychiatrist who analyzed the
letters for the newspaper, said they give a clear understanding of
Gacy's personality.
   ``He doesn't discuss the (murder) case in the letters, but they
show the mechanics of his personality like what makes a watch
tick,'' Ziporyn said.
   ``I think what's important is that he's `John Wayne' Gacy. John
Wayne like the movie star, and his trying to live up to that image
is an important part of his personality,'' Ziporyn said.
</TEXT>
