<HEAD>Suharto Swears In New Armed Forces Commander</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One name correct for Suharto, Sukarno, Sudharmono. Benny cq
as second reference for Gen. Benny Murdani</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Suharto on Saturday swore in
Gen. Try Sutrisno as the new commander of Indonesia's armed forces,
replacing Gen. Benny Murdani.
   Before his appointment as commander, Sutrisno was army chief.
   Presidential spokesman Sudharmono said Benny will continue to
serve as commander of the National Security Agency at least until
the end of the 11-day session of the People's Congress, which is
scheduled to begin Tuesday.
   The National Security Agency was formed in 1966 to restore order
after an unsuccessful communist-supported coup attempt the previous
year. Suharto was appointed its first commander by the late
President Sukarno.
   Benny became commander of the armed forces and of the security
agency in March 1983.
