<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 2243EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PalimonyPrizes     02-27 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Palimony Prizes,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Awards Half Of Lotto Jackpot To Winner's Ex-Housemate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MASON, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge ordered the winner of a $1.8 million
lottery jackpot to pay half the prize to his former live-in
girlfriend.
   Ingham County Circuit Judge Peter Houk upheld a claim Friday by
Carolyn Eeles of Westland that she and her ex-boyfriend, James W.
Renfro, had an oral agreement to share any winnings from the
Michigan Lotto tickets they bought Dec. 18, 1985.
   One of those tickets turned out to be the jackpot winner. But
Eeles' lawyer, Karl Nickolai, said Renfro returned to his estranged
wife less than two days after claiming all the prize money and then
moved to Tennessee.
   Houk said Renfro testified during the trial that he bought the
Lotto tickets himself. But the judge said 17 other witnesses
contradicted Renfro's testimony, including some who vouched for
Eeles' claim that she and Renfro each paid $5 for 10 tickets and
that Eeles herself picked the winning numbers.
   Renfro was ordered to pay Eeles half of the first two after-tax
installments, worth about $74,000 each, that he has collected. Houk
also ordered that Eeles receive half of the remaining 18 payments
and interest on the first two installments, and that Renfro pay her
lawyer's fees.
   ``I'm thrilled _ there is justice in this land,'' Eeles, 43,
said afterward. Renfro, 48, said the witnesses ``weren't telling
the truth.''
</TEXT>
