<HEAD>Carbon Monoxide Kills Four Children, Baby Sitter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd, 4th, 5th grafs to CORRECT name to Weerts, sted
Weerst, picking up 6th graf, `They were...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GREEN COVE SPRINGS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four children and their baby
sitter were killed by carbon monoxide fumes from a faulty gas
heater, officials said Saturday.
   Ola Weerts and a friend had left the children with a baby sitter
Friday night and went to dinner.
   ``They came back and checked about 9:30 p.m., left again and
arrived shortly before midnight and found the majority of them
dead,'' said Clay County Sheriff's Lt. Tim Martin.
   Pronounced dead at Mrs. Weerts' home here were two of her three
children, 10-year-old James and 6-year-old Sherri. Her friend's
granddaughter, Julie Meador, 10, and baby sitter Jennifer Bias, 17,
were also dead, Martin said.
   The third Weerts child, 12-year-old Tanya, died Saturday evening
at Shands Hospital in nearby Gainesville.
   ``They were all in their beds, apparently sleeping, except for
one 10-year-old on the kitchen floor,'' Martin said. Ms. Bias was
found on a living room sofa.
   ``It's absolutely the worst multiple death case in one family
that we've had in Clay County,'' Martin said.
   An autopsy on Tanya was scheduled for Sunday. Autopsies on the
others showed they died of acute carbon monoxide poisoning,
authorities said.
   ``A normal carbon monoxide level was 1 to 2 percent, caused by
pollutants like ozone,'' Martin said. ``Smokers have higher level,
maybe 10 percent.''
   ``The four kids had an average of 65 percent,'' he said.
   ``Ultimately, what has happened was, we feel, a faulty exhaust
on a gas furnace became clogged and the carbon monoxide fumes were
allowed to back up and disperse through the house,'' Martin said.
</TEXT>
