<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-DePaul     02-27 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-De Paul,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Composer, Pianist Gene Vincent de Paul Dead at 68</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Composer, pianist and musical arranger Gene
Vincent de Paul, whose collaboration with lyricist Don Raye on
``Pigfoot Pete'' got them an Oscar nomination, died Saturday after
a lengthy illness, his daughter said.
   De Paul, who was 68 and had been suffering from a brain tumor,
died at his suburban Northridge home, daughter April Leach said.
   He often collaborated with Raye, and the two were nominated for
an Academy Award in 1942 for the song ``Pigfoot Pete'' from the
film ``Hellzapoppin.''
   De Paul worked with Johnny Mercer on music for the 1954 film
``Seven Brides for Seven Brothers'' and the Broadway play, ``L'il
Abner.'' De Paul also worked on the music for the Walt Disney film,
``The Legend of Sleepy Hollow,'' Ms. Leach said.
   De Paul was inducted into the Songwriters' Hall of Fame in 1985,
Ms. Leach said. He was born in New York on June 17, 1919.
   ``He's had his music recorded from everybody from big bands to
Phoebe Snow and Stevie Wonder,'' Ms. Leach said. ``The Judds'
latest album has one of his songs on it.''
   Among his biggest hits were ``Cow Cow Boogie,'' ``Star Eyes,''
``Irresistible,'' ``When You're in Love'' and ``Mr. Five by Five.''
   He is survived by his daughter, three sons and two
grandchildren. A funeral was tentatively planned for Thursday, Ms.
Leach said.
  
</TEXT>
