<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Senegal-Elections     02-27 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senegal-Elections,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senegalese Election Campaign Closes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY LARRY JAMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAKAR, Senegal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senegal's violence-marred electioneering
ended Friday with President Abdou Diouf, the heavy favorite, making
a final campaign speech before an overflow crowd at the 30,000-seat
Demba Diop sports stadium.
   Diouf was expected to be re-elected and retain his Socialist
Party's majority in the National Assembly in elections Sunday.
   Four presidential candidates and six of Senegal's 17 registered
political parties were to contest the multiparty presidential and
National Assembly elections.
   A crowd estimated at more than 10,000 went to Senegal's
Independence Monument in this capital city Friday to attend a final
rally for the main opposition candidate, Abdoulaye Wade, and his
Senegalese Democratic Party.
   Security was increased following two days of violence in Thies,
42 miles northeast of Dakar. Truckloads of members of the Military
Intervention Group were stationed along Dakar's streets.
   The riot police were deployed against Democratic Party
supporters in two days of running battles in Thies, after the
government barred a rally by Wade's party in the town's main
square. Troops used tear gas, rubber bullets and truncheons to
scatter groups of stone-throwing youths.
   Some Democrats claimed more than 100 people, including eight
local party officials, were arrested. Government official did not
comment on the allegations.
   Diouf denounced his opponents, primarily Wade, at a rally Friday
morning in Thies at the Place de France, site of the earlier
clashes.
   ``In light of the events of yesterday, I am ashamed of
Senegal,'' said Diouf. ``I thought I was facing men who thought as
I did .... Unfortunately, these men are men of subversion.''
   A Socialist Party spokesman refused to comment when asked why
Diouf was allowed to speak in Thies while then opposition rally was
barred.
   Most of those who fought the riot forces were teen-agers.
   Brawling began Thursday.
   By Friday, the youths had armed themselves with sticks and wore
motorcycle helmets in preparation for street fighting. During
Diouf's 10-minute address in Thies, the concussion of exploding
tear gas canisters could be heard in the surrounding neighborhood.
The level of violence Friday appeared less intense than the day
before, though minor injuries were reported.
   The Socialists were expected to lose some of their 111 seats in
the 120-member assembly Sunday, although the 52-year-old Diouf was
expected to win easy re-election to a second five-year term.
   He has led Senegal since 1981, when the nation's first
president, Leopold Sedar Senghor, retired. Diouf won the 1983
elections with 83.5 percent of the vote to Wade's 14.79 percent.
Three other candidates shared the rest. Wade accused Diouf's party
of rigging the elections, a charge the president denied.
   Wade, 61, a lawyer and three-time presidential candidate,
accuses Diouf of selling out the country to Western creditors and
foreign businessmen.
   Wade threatened to turn his party into ``a liberation movement''
if he considered this election to have been rigged.
   Two million of Senegal's estimated 7 million people are
registered to vote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
