<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Soviet     02-27 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Soviet,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungarian Writers' Union Signs Agreement With Soviet Counterpart</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary and the Soviet Union pledged
friendship and support for each other Friday as a five-day visit by
Soviet President Andrei Gromyko drew to a close.
   And according to an unexpected announcement by both countries,
the Hungarian Writers' Union, which a year ago ran into political
trouble after it rejected conservatives in its leadership, signed a
working agreement with the Soviet Writers' Union.
   The friendship pledge came in a final communique signed by
Gromyko and President Karoly Nemeth of Hungary.
   Gromyko is to return to Moscow on Saturday, ending his first
foreign state visit since assuming the presidency in 1985.
   The agreement between the writers' unions means they will
cooperate in publishing books, exchange visits and sponsor
exchanges of students and critics.
   ``We are ahead of you'' in terms of glasnost, or openness,
Viktor Karpov, head of the Soviet Writer's Union, chided his
Hungarian audience at a news conference.
   Earlier, in an interview with a Hungarian newspaper, Karpov
noted that the Hungarian Writer's Union ``has successfully put
behind it the difficulties that had arisen within it.''
   Last year, more than 25 Communist Party loyalists left the
association of about 600 members. Culture Minister Bela Koepeczi
said the union no longer represented Hungary's literary sector
after writers chose to elect an independent board, rejecting board
members favored by the party.
   The state then authorized formation of a guild of writers, poets
and translators.
   The head of the Hungarian Union, Tibor Cseres, said Friday that
in the end a ``compromise was reached and neither side had to yield
its basic ground.''
   He said the compromise made possible the agreement with the
Soviet Writers' Union.
</TEXT>
