<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Art     02-27 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Art,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Art Museum Director Resigns Over Religious Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGIO CARRASCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Museum of Modern Art's director has
resigned because of protests about an exhibition in which a printed
face of Marilyn Monroe was imposed on an image of the Virgin of
Guadalupe, patron saint of Mexico.
   More than 100 artists and intellectuals issued a statement
Friday expressing ``profound indignation'' and demanded
reinstatement of Jorge Alberto Manrique.
   They blamed his resignation on ``the pressure exerted by
reactionary groups'' and said ``the director of a museum cannot ..
. be raised to be the censor of any work of art,'' the liberal
newspaper La Jornada reported.
   The government, which runs the museum, requested Manrique's
resignation Thursday and he complied.
   On Jan. 23, about 1,000 people chanting ``Long Live Christ the
King!'' stormed the museum in the Chapultepec Park and forced the
management to close an exhibit called ``Alternative Spaces'' by
Rolando de la Rosa, 36.
   He had superimposed the face of the late actress Marilyn Monroe
on an image of the Virgin of Guadalupe, an object of reverence in
Mexico where 90 percent of the 80 million citizens are Roman
Catholic.
   In another work, styled after Leonardo da Vinci's ``Last
Supper,'' Jesus Christ had the face of the late Mexican actor and
singer Pedro Infante. In ``La Sagrada Familia'' the baby Jesus was
replaced by a soccer ball.
   Pro-Vida, the group that organized the museum assault, demanded
the resignations of Manrique and Martin Reyes Vayssade,
undersecretary of culture. It also demanded de la Rosa be
hospitalized for ``social re-education.''
   Manrique was the only official of the government's Fine Arts
Institute, which runs the museum, to condemn the closing of the
exhibition, La Jornada said.
   It quoted him as calling for legal action against the
protesters, whom he described as ``neo-fascists with clear
political objectives.''
   ``Inevitably this decision will be interpreted as a pat on the
back for the attackers of museums,'' the newspaper quoted him as
saying about the forced resignation.
   Earlier, Manrique told the weekly magazine Proceso: ``To say the
Mexican people were offended (by the art) is a big lie and absurd.''
</TEXT>
