<HEAD>Miss USA Pageant Host Assaulted in Elevator</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with comments from Scoggins on the bail.
No pickup. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Tracy Scoggins was attacked in a
hotel elevator while in town to serve as a co-host of the Miss USA
Pageant, police said Friday.
   Miss Scoggins, who played Monica Colby in the ABC series ``The
Colbys,'' suffered bruises in the attack Thursday night, said
police Lt. J.R. Grijalva. She did not require medical attention.
   Antonio Garcia, 35, was charged with attempted sexual assault
and released on $100 bail set by Adolfo Romero, an associate
magistrate, Grijalva said.
   Miss Scoggins expressed outrage at what she considered low bail.
   ``What that says to me is that a man like this can save himself
a whole expensive night of dinner and dancing and just pay $100 to
assault the woman of his choice,'' she said. ``That's a pretty good
deal.''
   Romero was not in his office late Friday.
   Police said Garcia had followed Miss Scoggins to the Marriott
Hotel, where she was staying, and into the elevator.
   ``He pulled down the front of her evening gown and attempted to
sexually assault her,'' Grijalva said. ``She was able to fight him
off, and when the door opened, she was able to get out and call for
help.''
   Hotel guests pulled the man out of the elevator and subdued him
until hotel security and police arrived, Grijalva said.
   Miss Scoggins was attacked after returning from a taping of the
evening gown and swimsuit competitions.
   The 51 contestants have been staying in another hotel. Miss USA
will be crowned Tuesday night in a nationally broadcast pageant.
</TEXT>
