<1ST_LINE>r i AM--DirectAction     02-27 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM--Direct Action,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Sentences Suspected Terrorist to Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special court convicted and sentenced five people
Friday for three armed robberies in 1983 designed to help finance
the left-wing terrorist group Direct Action.
   The sentences _ life imprisonment for one defendent and 13 years
for each of the four others _ ended a two-week series of trials of
suspected Direct Action members.
   A sixth defendant was given a suspended sentence.
   Regis Schleicher, 31, was given a life sentence and Prosecutor
Daniel Barreyre called him ``a commando chief who shoots like a
professional, the most dangerous of the group.''
   Police considered Schleicher a founding member of Direct Action.
The terrorist group has asserted responsibility for numerous
bombings, the 1986 fatal shooting of Renault president Georges
Besse and the 1985 killing of French Gen. Rene Audran.
   Barreyre had asked for 20-year prison terms for each of the
other four: Jean-Marc Rouillan, 35, on his 88th day of a hunger
strike; Vincenzo Spano, 31; Nicolas Halfen, 24, and his brother,
Claude, 32.
   The sixth defendant, Frederique Germain, 31, cooperated with
police and received a five-year suspended prison term.
   A seven-judge court deliberated just over two hours before
handing down the convictions and sentences.
   The six were convicted of robbing two banks and a jewelry shop
in 1983. The holdups netted about $100,000, police said.
   In one robbery, two policemen were wounded and a member of the
gang was killed in a gun fight.
   Rouillan began a hunger strike Dec. 1, along with three other
suspected Direct Action members, to protest being kept in isolation
in prison.
   On Thursday, France's human rights minister, Claude Malhuret,
said the hunger strike campaign ``plays on the humanitarian
sentiments of the French people and must be stopped.''
   He said that despite their confinement, the defendants had the
right to daily walks, to receive newspapers, listen to the radio
and receive visits from family members, lawyers and doctors.
   The defendents were arrested by police Feb. 21, 1987, at a Loire
Valley farm. Authorities said Direct Action terrorist activities
ended with the arrests.
   The three other people on hunger strike are suspected of being
Direct Action leaders. In previous trials, seven suspected Direct
Action members were convicted on various lesser charges and given
prison sentences.
</TEXT>
