<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Latin-Contras     02-27 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Latin-Contras,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Countries Urge U.S. to Suspend Aid to Nicaraguan Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER BAENA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARTAGENA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven Latin American countries asked
the United States Friday to halt all aid to the rebels fighting
Nicaragua's leftist government.
   The foreign ministers of Argentina, Brazil, Colombia, Mexico,
Peru, Uruguay and Venezuela also signed a declaration calling for a
United Nations agreement to fight drug trafficking.
   Several foreign ministers indirectly criticized Panama's
military strongman, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, after Noriega's
allies deposed civilian President Eric Arturo Delvalle early Friday.
   The nations are members of the Group of Eight, formed last year
to assist Central American peace efforts. The group ended its
three-day meeting in Cartagena Friday.
   Panama, the eighth member, was not represented after Foreign
Minister Jorge Abadia left Cartagena Thursday night because of the
political crisis.
   The group's formal declaration made no mention of the Panamanian
turmoil, which began Thursday when Delvalle ordered Noriega to step
down from his post as military chief and Noriega refused.
   But Foreign Minister German Nava Carrillo of Venezuela made an
indirect reference to Noriega, saying that in a democracy ``the
military must be obedient to civilian power.''
   Foreign Minister Julio Londono Paredes of Colombia, who did not
mention Panama specifically, said democracy has suffered a blow in
Latin America.
   The ministers' statement recognized ``the value of the
contribution to the peace process'' that President Oscar Arias of
Costa Rica made with a peace plan signed last Aug. 7 by the five
Central American presidents.
   But the statement said fighting continues, countries are
building up armaments and ``destabilizing actions and violations of
international rights'' occur.
   Sources close to the foreign ministers told The Associated Press
that the reference to destabilizing actions and violations of
international rights was a reference to U.S. aid to the Nicaraguan
rebels known as Contras.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
ministers expressed concern in their talks about alleged Cuban
support of Salvadoran rebels. But the final declaration made no
mention of Cuban involvement in Central America.
   According to U.S. officials, there are some 8,000 Soviet bloc
and Cuban personnel in Nicaragua, including about 3,500 military
and secret police. More than 40,000 people have been killed in the
6-year-old civil war.
   El Salvador claims that Cuba is supporting Salvadoran rebels
with aid coming through Nicaragua.
   Referring to negotiations between the Nicaraguan government and
Nicaraguan rebels, the formal statement said that for the talks to
succeed there must be no interference from outside Central America.
   The statement urged developed nations to contribute emergency
aid to Central American countries.
</TEXT>
