<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 0056EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Cairns     02-27 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Cairns,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alfonsin Closes Summit With Criticism Of U.S., Common Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN CARLOS DE BARILOCHE, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Raul
Alfonsin said Friday that agricultural subsidies by the United
States and the European Economic Community have cost Argentina $12
billion since 1980.
   ``You have forgotten the developing world,'' Alfonsin told the
Cairns Group of 14 food-exporting nations on the last day of a
three-day meeting.
   The agricultural subsidies create economic and social unrest
that endangers the political stability of some countries, Alfonsin
said.
   Alfonsin criticized trade proposals by the United States and
European Common Market countries to begin reducing farm subsidies
as too little and too late.
   He said he didn't believe a U.S. proposal to eliminate farm
subsidies over 10 years ``can be considered definite,'' and the EEC
proposal to limit grain production to 160 million tons is about the
same grain production figure as last year.
   The Cairns Group ``has the central object of eliminating that
arsenal of protectionist measures that distorts foreign trade in
the field of agriculture,'' the president said.
   The group takes its name from the Australian coastal city where
the first ministerial-level meeting of the organization was held in
August 1986.
   It issued a closing declaration outlining its hopes for a
strategy to reduce trade protectionism. The declaration will be
introduced at the meeting of the General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade group next month.
   The Cairns Group also agreed to meet again in December in
Toronto.
   Also calling for the reduction or elimination of agricultural
trade protectionism was Grains Minister Charlie Mayer of Canada.
Trade Ministers Mike Moore of New Zealand and Michael Duffy of
Australia made similar declarations earlier at the meetings.
   The nations in the Cairns Group are Argentina, Australia,
Brazil, Canada, Chile, Colombia, Fiji, Hungary, Indonesia,
Malaysia, New Zealand, the Philippines, Thailand and Uruguay.
   Only Fiji among the 14 did not send a representative to
Bariloche, a mountain resort 1,000 miles southwest of Buenos Aires.
</TEXT>
