<2ND_LINE>AM-Campus Protests,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Occupations Continue At Hampshire College, University Of
Dayton</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Minority students occupying a Hampshire College office vowed
Friday to continue the four-day sit-in through the weekend, while
University of Dayton students held the president's office in a
protest against CIA recruiting.
   The Hampshire College students were attempting to pressure the
private school in Amherst, Mass., to do more to promote racial
harmony.
   Anita Fearman, a spokeswoman for the 40 students who took over
an office in a dormitory Tuesday, said discussions with college
President Adele Simmons have been cordial, but she saw no quick end
to the standoff.
   The students' demands include funding and a full-time
coordinator for their activities on behalf of minority students,
hiring of an administrator for multicultural affairs, a policy
statement condemning racism and amnesty for the protest.
   ``The administration has offered us $25,000 to reorganize and
make fundamental structural changes in the social fabric of the
college,'' Ms. Fearman said. ``It's going to take a lot more money
than that and we know they have the resources.''
   Simmons has said some of the demands, such as a policy on racial
harassment, have been in the works for several months. About 100 of
the college's 1,100 students are minorities.
   In Dayton, about 50 members of Plowshares for Peace and the
Democratic Socialists of America took over the outer office
Thursday of Brother Raymond L. Fitz, the Roman Catholic school's
president, and demanded a one-year moratorium on CIA recruitment.
   The number had dwindled to 27 by Friday, university spokeswoman
Teri Rizvi said.
   The students who remained were charged with disruption under the
student conduct code, Ms. Rizvi said. Penalties could range from a
fine to expulsion, and will be determined by a student-faculty
panel, she said.
   Fitz met with the protesters for 1{ hours Friday and said he
would discuss their demands with administrators and faculty.
   Schuerman told the protesters later: ``Whatever the resolution
is, it's not going to hinge on whether you stay here or leave.''
   Last week, students at the University of Massachusetts occupied
a building for six days to protest racial violence at the campus.
The siege ended with an agreement on such demands as increased
resources for Third World programs.
</TEXT>
