<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Elderly-Shooting     02-27 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Elderly-Shooting,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Charged In Shooting At Retirement Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 79-year-old man was charged with
attempted murder Friday after he stormed into a retirement home
that had evicted him for being a troublemaker and opened fire,
wounding four people, police said.
   William H. ``Shorty'' Cox was ordered held on $250,000 bond in
the shootings. Police said Cox burst in during a board meeting
Thursday.
   ``He picked out the people he felt had done him wrong and began
firing,'' police spokesman Dee Anderson said.
   Four people suffered minor gunshot wounds and a fifth, Willie
Joe Wright, 67, suffered a heart attack and was listed in critical
condition Friday at Arlington Memorial Hospital.
   Cox had lived in the home for 22 months but was evicted in
September for `violent acts,'' including shoving others and using
profane language, said Sam Hilburn, president of the home's board
of directors.
   ``I heard the rounds going off _ ping, ping, ping _ and saw
people ducking,'' said Pat Wilkinson, an electrician who phoned
authorities. ``I was still on the phone when he wandered through
the office. He said, `Go ahead and call the police ... I don't want
to get everything blown out of proportion.'''
   The home, which houses 140 people, has no security guards. Cox
entered the board room, where about 15 people were gathered, with a
semiautomatic rifle in his hands and another rifle strung around
his neck, police said.
   ``He said, `I've got a statement to make,' but rambled
incoherently,'' said board member Charles Smith.
   Cox shot once into the ceiling then ``apparently he selected
people and shot at them,'' Anderson said. ``It was not random
shooting.''
   Cox surrendered to police in a kitchen at the home, Anderson
said.
   Cox had sued the home, alleging that he had been wrongfully
evicted, but the suit was dismissed, Hilburn said.
</TEXT>
