<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Remember EDB? Four years after the grain fumigant
was banned as a possible cancer risk amid panic over contaminated
popcorn, breakfast cereal and muffin mix, the public has nearly
forgotten it.
   Judy Heckman, chief of pesticide disposal for the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency, hasn't. Heckman plans to fly to
Texas to preside at the burning of the last 330,000 gallons of the
pesticide early next week.
   The EDB, or ethylene dibromide, to be incinerated was taken from
a warehouse and put on a train in Liberty, Mo., that left last week
for an industrial park in Deer Park outside Houston. More trains
will leave with the remaining gallons every Monday until June,
officials said.
