<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:Vadim Adv03   02-27 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Vadim, Adv 03,0816</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thu AMs, March 3 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>And Vadim Created Woman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-one years ago, Brigitte Bardot wrapped her
voluptuous body in a sheet, tantalizing moviegoers around the world
who flocked to see France's new ``sex kitten'' in the film made by
her director-husband, Roger Vadim.
   The film, ``And God Created Woman,'' became a movie classic,
launched BB's career and defined the tone and content for the
director's subsequent films.
   Vadim has gone back to the same title for his latest film, which
has little in common with the 1956 version except a continuing
fascination with freedom, sensuality and bourgeois morality.
   If this sounds a bit pedantic, remember that Vadim is the
filmmaker who gave the world the avant-garde sci-fi romp
``Barbarella'' starring his young, blond wife, Jane Fonda.
   His films are never short on beauty, especially the blond,
blue-eyed kind. Vadim has cast his 26 movies with women ranging
from elegant Catherine Deneuve, his third wife, to earthy Angie
Dickinson, and from intellectual Jeanne Moreau to sexpot Susan
Sarandon.
   For the new ``And God Created Woman,'' which opens this month in
the United States, Vadim chose blond Rebecca DeMornay, whose
previous credits include playing the saucy strumpet opposite Tom
Cruise in ``Risky Business'' and the angelic girl next door in
``The Trip to Bountiful.''
   ``People tell Rebecca that she has never looked more beautiful
than in this film,'' said Vadim, the Gallic Svengali, as he relaxed
in a borrowed Paris apartment after a morning of television
interviews. ``But it wasn't intentional. I make people look
beautiful, I can't help it.
   ``You wouldn't ask Rodin to make an ugly sculpture, or me to
make a film with an ugly woman. That's my style, that's my nature.''
   Bardot played a woman who marries a man in order to escape an
orphanage, only to fall for the man's younger brother, played by
Jean-Louis Trintignent. Although in the end she remains with her
older husband, the film is an exploration of sexual freedom.
   ``I wanted to show a normal young girl whose only difference was
that she behaved in the way a boy might, without any sense of guilt
on a moral or sexual level,'' Vadim said. ``There was really
nothing shocking in what Brigitte did, what was provocative was her
natural sensuality.''
   Vadim said sexual liberty is taken for granted now and women in
the 1980s are fighting for freedom of a different sort. He said he
didn't want to remake his earlier film but wanted to illuminate the
problems faced by a modern, young woman.
   ``Women now seek the freedom to be themselves, to be successful
in work without renouncing old-fashioned romanticism. Women want to
keep what they have gained without giving up those romantic ideas
which are very nice in life,'' said the 60-year-old Vadim, who
looks more like a French lawyer in his gray slacks and navy
pullover than an international film director.
   The film, shot in Santa Fe, N.M., tells the story of a young,
female prisoner who meets a carpenter working at the jail and
marries him as a way to show she is a stable candidate for parole.
   Her husband is nice, but chauvinistic, and the film follows
their relationship to an ``optimistic end, where they can stay
together without her giving up herself.''
   Vadim moved to Malibu, Calif., after his divorce from Fonda and
rented a house across from her so the two could share in the
raising of their daughter. He also has children by Deneuve and his
second wife, Annette Stroyberg.
   During the interview, he talked about the movie industry and
said his counterparts in French film lack the professionalism that
characterizes Hollywood. He pointed out that 1987 was one of the
worst years in a decade for box-office receipts in France, while
the opposite was true in the United States.
   ``French filmmakers are beginning to realize they have to try
harder, put more thought and effort into their films and make them
more international,'' he said.
   Vadim has been asked by several Paris producers to shoot his
next film in France and is considering making a science-fiction
film or suspense thriller here in English.
   ``But you know I've never had great luck in France. When `And
God Created Woman' was released the critics were horrible,
especially to Brigitte who they said couldn't act,'' he said. ``Of
course she couldn't, but she had another quality, she was and is
inimitable, unique.''
   After the film was an international success, the French critics
changed their minds, he said.
   ``I am sure that these same critics will aggress my new movie,
saying, `how can you touch such a classic, French masterpiece?'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, March 3</NOTE>
