<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Wall Street, Adv 27-28,0618</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 27</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Feb 27-28</NOTE>
<HEAD>Takeovers Give Some Sparkle to a Drab Stock Market</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the hopes of many Wall Street analysts are
borne out, corporate takeovers will provide an important source of
support for the stock market all through 1988.
   In just the first two months of the year, the pot has kept
bubbling with bids for the likes of Sterling Drug, Federated
Department Stores and Stop & Shop.
   Brokers like these stories because they have enlivened what has
otherwise been a very sluggish and scared stock market in the
aftermath of the crash last fall.
   When one company in a given industry _ for example,
Addison-Wesley in publishing _ receives a bid, other stocks with
similar businesses tend to attract speculative buying.
   But beyond the windfalls takeovers can produce for holders of an
individual stock, analysts see these deals as positive for the
overall market outlook.
   For one thing, they say, the activity suggests that a fair-sized
number of presumably sophisticated people view American stocks as
attractively priced.
   Furthermore, takeovers can have a sort of echo effect. When the
holders of a company that is acquired get paid off, they are likely
to reinvest the proceeds in other stocks.
   ``The takeover game is going like gangbusters,'' observed Jay
Donnaruma, an analyst at First Albany Corp. in Albany, N.Y.
``Apparently everyone wants to `make a deal' before the environment
in Washington changes and becomes less friendly.
   ``The takeovers do create more money to go into stocks, and
that's a positive for the near future.''
   Joseph Feshback, technical analyst at Prudential-Bache
Securities, cites takeovers as one reason why he thinks a dramatic
rise in the stock market ``could occur any week now.''
   ``This is the final year of an administration that has been very
accommodating to takeovers,'' he says. ``If takeovers proceed at a
very rapid pace, they will put a huge supply of liquidity into the
system.
   ``By my rough calculations, as much as $20 billion could be
injected back into the system this year. Most of this should
eventually find a home in the equity market.''
   Stocks struggled to make much headway in the past week. The Dow
Jones average of 30 industrials edged up 8.62 to 2,023.21.
   The New York Stock Exchange composite index gained .74 to
147.70; the American Stock Exchange market value index rose 4.07 to
284.23; and the NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market increased 6.28 to 363.40.
   Volume on the Big Board averaged 191.09 million shares a day,
against 160.98 million the week before.
   The merits and demerits of takeovers, of course, have been hotly
debated for years. One question many observers are asking these
days: How many American assets do we want to sell to foreign
investors to help finance our habit of consuming beyond our means?
   Nevertheless, it appears to be a fact of life at the moment that
the depressed dollar in foreign exchange is attracting foreign
buyers to U.S. businesses.
   Some see buying by corporations, either domestic or foreign, as
preferable to the formerly fashionable leveraged buyout, in which
big investors used huge amounts of debt to acquire businesses.
   However they are conducted, mergers and acquisitions tend to
reduce the supply of stock available in the marketplace.
   And if you take the simple Economics 1 view that prices of
stocks are determined by supply and demand, a shrinking supply
becomes a force working in favor of higher prices.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Feb. 27-28</NOTE>
</DOC>
