<NOTE>For Release AMs Monday Feb. 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>Newly Started Construction Falls in January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The value of newly started construction fell 8
percent in January from the previous month, led by a steep drop in
non-residential buildings, a construction research concern said
Sunday.
   The F.W. Dodge division of McGraw-Hill Information Systems Co.
said the latest decline continued a downward drift from highs
reached last August.
   The report said the annualized value of new construction
contracts fell to $228 billion in January from $247.3 billion in
December 1987.
   On a seasonally adjusted basis, contracts for non-residential
building tumbled 16 percent to $75.6 billion, residential
construction fell 3 percent to $110.4 billion and public works
construction fell 4 percent to $42.0 billion.
   ``January's contracting data reinforced the downward trend of
new construction activity which has been developing since the
fall,'' said George A. Christie, vice president and chief economist
for F.W. Dodge.
   He said construction contracting has fallen on a month-to-month
basis in three of the past five months since reaching an August
peak of $273.1 billion.
   Contracting for new construction is viewed as a leading
indicator of spending and employment throughout the construction
industry.
   Christie said a decline in January's contracting for
non-residential buildings reflected a bigger than expected decline
in the commercial construction market.
   ``It's been a tough winter especially throughout the South where
starts were weak, so part of January's steep fall may have been
weather related,'' he said. He said he expected non-residential
contracting ``will be ratcheting its way down over the rest of
1988.''
   Non-residential construction also includes buildings for
industrial, manufacturing, educational, religious and recreational
puposes.
   The decline in residential contracting reflected stability in
one-family home building and continued declines for apartments and
hotels, the report said. Dodge expects total housing starts will
fall 5 percent in all of 1988 to 1.525 million units.
   The drop in contracting for public works projects and other
``non-building'' construction reflected a stabilization in highway
and bridge construction.
   That figure also includes contruction of dams, sewage and water
supply systems, airports and utility and communication systems.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv AMs Monday Feb. 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
