<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-88 0638EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv27-28   02-27 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 27-28,0567</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 27</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Feb 27-28</NOTE>
<HEAD>Fed Slowly Lifting Cloak Of Secrecy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The poker-faced Federal Reserve let the public
peek at some of its cards this past week by providing specific
clues as to how monetary policy was being played out lately.
   Manuel H. Johnson, vice chairman of the Fed, confirmed that the
central bank was paying closer attention to fluctuations in the
dollar, commodity prices and the interest-rate yield curve, or the
difference in long- and short-term rates.
   Fed policy in recent years had involved watching a greater
variety of economic measures, such as the money supply, which
includes cash in circulation, checking and savings accounts and
money market accounts.
   While most Fed watchers had been aware of this change in
direction for some time _ seeing hints, for example, in minutes of
policy committee meetings or from central bank governors _ they
were heartened by the fact the Fed made this information available
to the public.
   ``God bless Johnson ... because we can all start thinking the
same way,'' said William V. Sullivan, director of money market
research for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``The Fed has operated in a
cloak of secrecy.''
   He said ``the new regime seems to be more open'' under Chairman
Alan Greenspan than it was under Paul A. Volcker, who left office
last summer.
   ``The Fed enjoys a certain amount of secrecy,'' said F. Ward
McCarthy, chief financial economist for Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets. ``The less the public knows ... the easier it is for it to
do its job.
   ``But I don't think it's always intentional. I think for a
period of time they couldn't decide exactly what was driving
monetary policy.''
   At a conference sponsored by the Cato Institute in Washington,
Johnson noted that the relationship between the money supply and
the economy has become less predictable in recent years. He
admitted that as a result there was always a mystery about what
numbers the Fed was watching, and that was unhealthy for the credit
markets.
   The value of the dollar, commodity prices and the yield-curve
might not be perfect indicators, Johnson said, but together they
provide a clearer picture of whether the economy is heating up.
   Economists say the Fed is likely to keep lowering interest rates
to stimulate the economy until the indicators point toward
inflation.
   The credit markets have been closely tracking those same
indicators for some time, pushing interest rates higher at the sign
of rising inflation and lower with sluggish economic growth.
   ``This reaffirms the perception that the markets are the
ultimate critic of monetary policy,'' said McCarthy.
   Johnson's remarks this past week means the Fed and the credit
markets are on the same wavelength, said Maria F. Ramirez, a top
economist at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., and they also provide a
clearer indication as to where rates might be heading.
   ``This could reduce volatility'' in bond prices, said Sullivan.
   But Carol A. Stone, senior economist for Nomura Securities Inc.,
said, ``It could mean somewhat more volatility because the markets
know the Fed is looking at particular things,'' and they might
overreact.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Feb 27-28</NOTE>
</DOC>
