<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Chrysler-Kenosha     02-27 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chrysler-Kenosha,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAW Local Sues Chrysler Over Planned Kenosha Plant Closing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Autoworkers Union Local 72 filed a
lawsuit Friday against Chrysler Corp., alleging the company is
breaking federal laws by pulling auto production from Kenosha and
putting 5,500 people out of work.
   In reponse, Chrysler said a preliminary review of the suit
indicated it was ``without merit.''
   The suit, which also names as defendants the city of Detroit and
the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development, said Chrysler
obtained about $50 million in federal grants to modernize its
Jefferson Avenue plant in Detroit, said James Eggleston, an
attorney for the union.
   He said that when Chrysler applied for the federal money, the
carmaker said it would make mid-sized trucks at the old Jefferson
Avenue plant to keep jobs there during the modernization of the
facility.
   But now the company plans to shift production of the L-body
Omni-Horizon cars to Detroit from Kenosha, he said. Chrysler
announced last month it planned to close the Kenosha plant by fall.
   ``The lawsuit is trying to prevent the use of federal funds to
destroy a community,'' Eggleston said.
   The suit was filed in U.S. District Court in Milwaukee, and it
seeks an injunction to force Chrysler to keep its plant in Kenosha
open while continuing its upgrading of the Jefferson Avenue plant.
   In its response, Chrysler said, ``Our lawyers have not had time
to thoroughly examine the complaint but based on a preliminary
review the lawsuit is without merit.''
   ``The government money is for the new Jefferson facility. No
government money will be spent at the old Jefferson plant where the
L-body (Omni-Horizon) will be produced,'' Chrysler said in the
statement.
   Bob Berg, spokesman for Detroit Mayor Coleman Young, said the
city has not received formal notification of the lawsuit and would
not comment until it was able to examine the filing.
   Chrysler announced late last month the Kenosha plant would close.
   Eggleston said $15 million of the federal money came under the
Urban Development Action Grant program, which he said cannot be
used to transplant jobs from one community to another.
   The remaining $35 million came under a community development
block grant, which Eggleston said requires an impact study be done
by the federal government and Detroit. The suit said that the grant
was approved without assessing ``the significant adverse effects on
the human environment in Kenosha.''
   Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca has offered to divert profits from
this year's car sales in Wisconsin to create a trust fund for the
laid off autoworkers. Iacocca also said while the automaker may
have raised expectations in Wisconsin, it made no promises to keep
the Kenosha plant open.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
