<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OilProduction     02-27 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Production,0170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Sees Decline in Oil Output in 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Final figures likely will show that Texas crude
oil production fell about 8 percent during 1987, the Texas Railroad
Commission reported Friday.
   Commission Chairman Jim Nugent said the state's oil production
still is suffering from the effects of the 1986 plunge in world oil
prices.
   ``Texas' oil production decline steepened in 1987. Final
production numbers should show a drop of 60 million barrels, or
about 8 percent, from 1986,'' Nugent said.
   A barrel is equivalent to 42 gallons.
   Nugent said the state's daily production rate fell 80,000
barrels a day between January and December 1987.
   ``That's not surprising when you look at the number of wells
that have been dropped off production over the last two years,'' he
said.
   ``Between the end of 1985 and the fall of last year, we lost
production from some 30,000 stripper wells and more than 9,000 of
the better-producing wells,'' Nugent said.
</TEXT>
