<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     02-27 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bearishness Dominates Oil Market, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices continue to be weighed down by an
overwhelming mood of bearishness in the market, analysts say.
   At the New York Mercantile Exchange Friday, contracts for April
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil,
closed at $15.78 per 42-gallon barrel, down 14 cents from Thursday.
   It was the second day in a row that the near-month crude
contract closed below $16 since Dec. 21, when it settled at $15.16.
   Among March contracts for refined products, wholesale heating
oil closed at 45.70 cents a gallon, up 0.48 cent from Thursday,
while wholesale unleaded gasoline settled at 45.26 cents a gallon,
0.11 cent lower.
   Heating oil was the only bright spot during the day, drawing
strong demand because of a perception that inventories are
``relatively low,'' said Andrew Lebow, an analyst at the Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. securities firm.
   But he said the prevailing sentiment ``is still bearish,''
adding that he joined other traders in expecting further declines
for crude prices next week.
   John O'Dea, manager of international energy futures at Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc., said his firm shared that view, citing
overproduction by OPEC as ``the overriding issue.''
   O'Dea said the 13 members of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries have been operating on an
``every-man-for-himself'' basis, producing as much oil as necessary
for their respective shares of the market, despite slack demand and
burgeoning inventories.
   As a result, he said, this has only increased downward pressure
on prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
